 (August)\n|Montgomery was last heard from August 26, 2010 when she called her parents to \"touch base.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unsolvedcanada.ca/index.php?topic=3894.0|title=Natasha Lynn Montgomery \u2013 Deceased \u2013 Still Missing|website=unsolvedcanada.ca|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref> She was known to be engaged in sex work. Serial killer Cody Legebokoff was convicted of her murder, though Natasha's body has never been found. Natasha's DNA was discovered on Legebokoff's shorts, hoodie, throughout his apartment, and on his axe.<ref name=\":4\" />\n|[[Cody Legebokoff]] was arrested on 27 November 2010 and convicted of first-degree murder on September 11, 2014.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> On September 11, 2014, Canadian serial killer [[Cody Legebokoff]] was convicted of first-degree murder in the deaths of Loren Donn Leslie, Jill Stacey Stuchenko, Cynthia Frances Maas and Natasha Lynn Montgomery.<ref name=\":2\" /> In September 2016 the BC Court of Appeal confirmed the original conviction.<ref name=\":36\" /> Legebokoff was age 20 when he was arrested.<ref name=\":44\" />\n|\n|-\n|Cynthia Frances Maas\n|35\n|Homicide\n|Prince George\n|2010 (September)\n|The remains of Cynthia Frances Maas were found in L.C. Gunn Park, near Prince George, on Oct. 8. Maas was last seen Sept. 10 in the area of Juniper Street and 19 Avenue In Prince George.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/police-id-body-found-in-prince-george-1.878473|title=Police ID body found in Prince George {{!}} CBC News|work=CBC|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref> She was reported missing by family members and friends on Sept. 23 after she failed to check in with them.<ref name=\":19\" /> She had died from blunt force trauma and penetrating wounds to the chest. She had defense wounds and her pants were rolled down to her ankles. She was known to be engaged in sex work.<ref name=\":4\" />\n|[[Cody Legebokoff]] was arrested on 27 November 2010 and con