bers and friends on Sept. 23 after she failed to check in with them.<ref name=\":19\" /> She had died from blunt force trauma and penetrating wounds to the chest. She had defense wounds and her pants were rolled down to her ankles. She was known to be engaged in sex work.<ref name=\":4\" />\n|[[Cody Legebokoff]] was arrested on 27 November 2010 and convicted of first-degree murder on September 11, 2014.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> On September 11, 2014, Canadian serial killer [[Cody Legebokoff]] was convicted of first-degree murder in the deaths of Loren Donn Leslie, Jill Stacey Stuchenko, Cynthia Frances Maas and Natasha Lynn Montgomery.<ref name=\":2\" /> In September 2016 the BC Court of Appeal confirmed the original conviction.<ref name=\":36\" /> Legebokoff was age 20 when he was arrested.<ref name=\":44\" />\n|\n|-\n|Linda Fredin\n|56\n|Homicide\n|Prince George\n|2010 (November)\n|Linda Fredin was trapped in her wheelchair when her home was consumed by fire on November 24, 2010. She was transported to Vancouver General Hospital where she died three days later.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|url=https://bc.ctvnews.ca/disabled-woman-burned-in-gang-arson-dies-1.582182|title=Disabled woman burned in gang arson dies|date=2010-12-03|work=British Columbia|access-date=2018-09-23}}</ref>\n|Police believe that the crime may have been linked to gang violence.<ref name=\":11\" />\n|\n|-\n|Loren Donn Leslie\n|15\n|Homicide\n|Vanderhoof\n|2010 (November)\n|Was an acquaintance of serial killer Cody Legebokoff, whom she met online. Her body was found in November 2010 on a remote logging road just off Highway 27 near Fort St James. Legebokoff was pulled over by police on November 27, 2010 and was in possession of Loren's belongings and covered in Loren's blood.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/blind-bc-victim-15-was-happy-hours-before-death-father-tells-murder-trial/article18967684/|title=RCMP officer's hunch 