rdi Bolduc. According to her own testimony, Jordi left Maddy there because Jordi was drunk and injured, and Maddy, already settled in for the night, didn't want to leave her sleeping bag. Maddy last communicated with others at the party around 4 am and was never heard from again. The next morning Jordi went back to the campsite, but didn't see Maddy. Jordi reported that she saw that Maddy's tent door was open and the bedding was pushed to one side. Not thinking much of it, Jordi went to work. More than a day later, Madison's parents went to check on Madison and reported her missing to the police shortly after discovering her abandoned truck and flattened tent at the lake. Numerous items of value were found on, in and around the truck, which included unopened liquor, gasoline, motorbike equipment, camera and purse. An iPhone 5 with a blue case and a set of keys with a gothic themed lanyard are among some of the items known to be missing. Police said that there was no sign of a struggle and that foul play is suspected.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://madisonscott.ca/|title = Help Find Madison Scott|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = Makepeace|first = Civility}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.princegeorgecitizen.com/news/local-news/madison-scott-missing-for-four-years-1.1951616|title = Prince George Citizen Local News|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = Makepeace|first = Civility}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n|Maria Practicante Rego\n|47\n|Homicide\n|[[Kitimat]]\n|2011 (October)\n|On October 9, 2011, around 7 a.m., Kitimat RCMP were called to a residence in the area of Whitesail road for an alleged break and enter with assault, whereby officers found a man and woman, who had been assaulted and were in need of immediate medical help. The woman, Maria Rego, succumbed to her injuries and died four days later; the man, her husband, survived. A 19-year-old man was arrested nearby without incident.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.terracestandard.com/news/kitimat-murderer-sentenced-to-life-in-prison/|title=Kitimat murderer sentenced to life in prison \u2013 Terrace Standard|date=2015-03-25|work=Terrace Standard|access-date=2018-10-10}}</ref>\n|Tyler Scott Eli was convicted to life imprisonment for second-degree murder on March 25, 2015.<ref name=\":22\" />\n|\n|-\n|Unnamed\n|\n|Unknown\n|[[Telkwa]]\n|2011 (November)\n|In the early morning of 11 November 2011, police and medical first responders were called to a scene at a road in Telkwa, where a woman was found in the middle of a road. The woman had received life-threatening injuries and later died in hospital. Said RCMP spokesperson Dan Moskaluk, \"Police are treating the death as possibly being criminal in nature and arrested an adult male who was found at the scene on police arrival.\" The man was taken into police custody Friday and released Saturday morning. Moskaluk said the woman and the man knew each other. No charges were laid at the time. The woman's body was flown to Vancouver for an autopsy. The results of the autopsy were not released to public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.interior-news.com/news/autopsy-details-not-being-released-regarding-telkwa-womans-death/|title=Autopsy details not being released regarding Telkwa woman's death|last=News|date=2011-11-24|website=Smithers Interior News|access-date=2018-12-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprovince.com/news/man-in-custody-after-telkwa-woman-dies|title=Man in custody after Telkwa woman dies {{!}} The Province|last=Province|first=The|last2=News|date=2011-11-12|access-date=2018-12-13|last3=Email|first3=Share Man in custody after Telkwa woman dies Tumblr Pinterest Google Plus Reddit LinkedIn|last4=Tumblr|last5=Pinterest|last6=Plus|first6=Google|last7=Reddit|last8=LinkedIn|last9=Email}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n|April Rose Johnson\n|18\n|Homicide\n|Vanderhoof\n|2012 (December)\n|Johnson was shot on the afternoon of Thursday, December 20, 2012, by her recently engaged fianc\u00e9, Kayne Sabbe Penner. The two had paid an unplanned visit to the home of Penner's cousin, Richard Borne, in the mid-afternoon to celebrate their engagement, as well as Borne's birthday and the holiday season. Borne's girlfriend, Patricia Heichert, also lived in the home, a single-wide mobile home in the 6200 block of McLeod Road in Vanderhoof. Penner claimed that the .22 calibre rifle which shot Johnson \"kind of just slipped, hit the counter and went off.\" A ballistics expert testified during Penner's trial that the rifle was not prone to discharging when dropped. Johnson arrived at the hospital, less than a 10-minute drive away, just before 4&nbsp;p.m. Johnson was shot in the upper left abdomen, and because her health was declining rapidly, she was transferred by ambulance to [[University Hospital of Northern British Columbia]], where she died shortly before 2&nbsp;a.m. on December 21. Penner's Facebook page indicated that he was seeing another woman within two months of the shooting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.princegeorgecitizen.com/news/local-news/it-happened-so-quickly-1.10823825|title=It happened so quickly|website=Prince George Citizen|access-date=2018-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.princegeorgecitizen.com/news/local-news/victim-and-accused-were-recently-engaged-manslaughter-trial-hears-1.10634390|title=Victim and accused were recently engaged, manslaughter trial hears|last=Nielsen|first=Mark|website=Prince George Citizen|access-date=2018-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.princegeorgecitizen.com/news/local-news/gun-owner-blames-himself-for-vanderhoof-woman-s-death-court-hears-1.10739845|title=Gun owner blames himself for Vanderhoof woman's death, court hears|last=Nielsen|first=Mark|website=Prince George Citizen|access-date=2018-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.princegeorgecitizen.com/news/local-news/shooting-death-yields-four-years-in-prison-1.22867259|title=Shooting death yields four years in prison|last=Nielsen|first=Mark|website=Prince George Citizen|access-date=2018-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.princegeorgecitizen.com/news/local-news/manslaughter-trial-hears-counsels-closing-arguments-1.10921448|title=Manslaughter trial hears counsels' closing arguments|last=Nielsen|first=Mark|website=Prince George Citizen|access-date=2018-12-29}}</ref>\n|In June 2015, Provincial Crown Counsel approved charges of manslaughter with a firearm and careless use of a firearm on 27-year-old Penner. The Crown also approved charges of careless storage of a firearm, careless use of a firearm and unauthorized possession of a firearm against 38-year-old Borne. The two were arrested shortly after charges were approved.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.burnslakelakesdistrictnews.com/news/two-men-arrested-for-shooting-death-of-18-year/|title=Two men arrested for shooting death of 18 year|date=2015-06-30|website=Burns Lake Lakes District News|access-date=2018-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kelownanow.com/watercooler/news/news/Provincial/15/06/27/B_C_Men_Arrested_in_Killing_of_18_Year_Old_Woman_in_2012/|title=B.C. Men Arrested in Killing of 18-Year-Old Woman in 2012|last=KelownaNow|website=KelownaNow|access-date=2018-12-29}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|Tara Lee Ann Williams\n|40\n|Homicide\n|Vanderhoof\n|2013 (January)\n|On January 13, 2013, the body of Williams, along with Blaine Albert Barfoot, were found at a home in Vanderhoof, BC. Police suspected foul play and soon after asked public to come forward with any information if anyone had seen someone with recently acquired injuries to their hands or arms (defensive wounds).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2013/01/16/vanderhoof-killings-blaine-barfoot-tara-williams-homicide_n_2491195.html|title=Vanderhoof Killings: Blaine Barfoot, Tara Williams Deaths Ruled A Double Homicide|date=2013-01-16|work=HuffPost Canada|access-date=2018-10-29}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n|Destiny Rae Tom\n|21\n|Homicide\n|[[Fraser Lake]]\n|2013 (March)\n|Was found dead On March 23, 2013 outside a home on the Nadleh Whut'en First Nation in northern B.C. She had been severely beaten. Destiny left behind one daughter.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.princegeorgecitizen.com/news/local-news/man-arrested-for-2013-death-of-destiny-rae-tom-1.1762818|title=Man arrested for 2013 death of Destiny Rae Tom|last=staff|first=Citizen|work=Prince George Citizen|access-date=2018-10-20}}</ref>\n|Garrett Steven George was charged in February 2015 of second-degree murder in the case. George had a criminal record that includes convictions for assault, assault with a weapon and assault causing bodily harm in Burns Lake and Prince George.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n|\n|-\n|[[Disappearance of Immaculate Basil|Immaculate \"Mackie\" Mary Basil]]\n|26\n|Missing\n|[[Tachie, British Columbia|Tachie]]\n|2013 (June)\n|Mother of a five-year-old son, \"Mackie\" had recently broke up with the father of the child, her common law husband. Her family described her as a \"home body\" who didn't have drug problems. The night she went missing, she was at a house party on Thursday 13 June 2013, a 20-minute walk away from her house in Tachie, she left at midnight. She was last seen after the house party, heading to a cabin in the Leo Creek area, north of Tachie. According to police reports from interviews with the men, Mackie was with two men, one her cousin Keith, and the other a man named Victor in a white truck, heading towards a cabin near Kuzche reserve. They had been drinking and were going to pickup tin. When the truck got stuck after an accident, she separated from the two and headed for the cabin alone. This is what was told to the police by Keith and Victor. Mackie would usually call her sisters every day at 10 am. Her sister, Chrystal became alarmed after a few days of not receiving a call. Mackie was reported missing to the RCMP Monday June 17, 2013 by Chrystal. The RCMP came to Fort St James to file a missing persons report on June 18, 2013. Mackie didn't bring an extra set of clothes or makeup, which she changed daily, and her family considers her disappearance to be out of character. The police had conducted a polygraph test of both Keith and Victor and reported that both were \"cooperative.\" A police psychologist also conducted an interview of both men, and reported to the public there was nothing suspicious. Numerous witnesses reported seeing Victor in Tachie at 10 am, 14 June 2013, the day of Mackie's disappearance, \"walking down the road, clothes wet up to his chest.\" Mackie went missing one hours drive away by vehicle from Fort St James, at a place called \"16 kilometer.\" It is not known how Victor got back to Tachie so soon without a vehicle.<ref>{{Citation|last=FM|first=Player|title=Immaculate Basil: At The After Party|url=https://player.fm/series/unfound-a-missing-persons-program/immaculate-basil-at-the-after-party|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n|Anita Florence Thorne\n|49\n|Missing\n|Prince George\n|2014 (November)\n|Thorne was reported missing on the evening of Wednesday 19 November 2014, at 8:15 PM. She was last seen that morning, at SuperSave Gas at 950 Victoria Street, then at a nearby Tim Horton's. RCMP found her car midday of the 20th at the turn off to Willow River, 30&nbsp;km away from where she was last seen. Her purse was inside the unlocked vehicle, and visible, with nothing apparently missing. She is believed to have her keys, cigarettes, lighter and cell phone (which had gone unanswered when called) in her possession. Anita was wearing a white hoodie with a black puffy vest, and with her brown hair up in a bun. She is Caucasian 157&nbsp;cm (5'2\") tall, weighing 66&nbsp;kg (145&nbsp;lbs), with brown eyes and brown shoulder length hair. Numerous people described her as someone who would \"give the shirt off her back\" to help someone in need.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unsolvedcanada.ca/index.php?topic=7388.0|title=Anita Thorne \u2013 49 \u2013 Missing \u2013 Car found at Willow River Rest area \u2013 PG, BC|website=unsolvedcanada.ca|access-date=2018-12-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.princegeorgecitizen.com/news/local-news/reward-fundraising-to-help-find-p-g-woman-1.1729030|title=Reward fundraising to help find P.G. woman|last=staff|first=Citizen|website=Prince George Citizen|access-date=2018-12-22}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n|Shirley Williams\n|77\n|Homicide\n|[[Granisle]]\n|2016 (April)\n|RCMP shot and killed Shirley and her son J\u00f4van Williams early on the afternoon of Thursday 21 April 2016. RCMP say they were called to a \"neighbour dispute involving a handgun\" at about 12:30&nbsp;p.m. PT. Police say they arrived at 1:22&nbsp;p.m., surrounded the home, and tried to make contact with the residents. They say one person exited the home and confronted officers, and shots were fired at 2:50&nbsp;p.m. A second person then exited the home and also confronted police, and shots were fired again. RCMP say both people died after being attended to by paramedics, who were nearby.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/police-incident-shooting-granisle-1.3547972|title=Mother and son dead after police incident in northern B.C.|date=Apr 21, 2016|website=CBC|access-date=2018-12-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/shirley-williams-77-and-son-jovan-williams-39-confirmed-as-victims-in-police-involved-shooting-1.3548521|title=Mother and son killed in police-involved shooting identified by family|last=April 22, 2016|website=CBC|access-date=2018-12-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/shirley-joven-williams-rcmp-1.3591705|title=Police shot Granisle mother and son, investigators confirm|last=May 20, 2016|website=CBC|access-date=2018-12-25}}</ref><ref name=\":37\">{{Cite web|url=http://cfnrfm.ca/iio-clears-rcmp-in-2016-granisle-standoff-shooting-deaths/|title=IIO clears RCMP in 2016 Granisle standoff shooting deaths|last=Fee|first=Bill|date=2018-06-08|website=CFNR :: First Nations Radio|access-date=2018-12-25}}</ref><ref name=\":38\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.interior-news.com/news/no-charges-in-granisle-police-shooting-deaths-of-mother-and-son/|title=No charges in police shooting deaths of Granisle mother and son|date=2018-06-08|website=Smithers Interior News|access-date=2018-12-25}}</ref>\n|A report released in 2018 by an independent civilian watchdog, the Independent Investigations Office, indicated that police used reasonable force to defend themselves. Indicating that the police responded to the threat of Mr Williams leveling a rifle and throwing a lit Molotov cocktail; in addition to the later threat of Mrs Williams levelling a shotgun at the officers. The IIO report added that both victims' bodies had firearms found beside them and there were the remains of a charred Molotov cocktail found nearby. No recommendations for charges were submitted to crown.<ref name=\":37\" /><ref name=\":38\" />\n|\n|-\n|Roberta (Robin) Marie Sims\n|55\n|Homicide\n|Prince George\n|2017 (May)\n|Sims, 55, was last seen by numerous witnesses on Saturday 6 May 2017. She was seen near her home at 3015-3rd Ave. across from Central Fort George Traditional School. She may have also been seen the BX Pub at Fifth and Carney and the Spruceland CIBC bank around the time she went missing, RCMP said. Sims was reported missing on Sunday 14 May 2017. RCMP stated that they believe Sims' vehicle was used in her murder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.princegeorgecitizen.com/news/local-news/police-seeking-public-s-help-as-woman-remains-missing-1.20421489|title=Police seeking public's help as woman remains missing|last=staff|first=Citizen|website=Prince George Citizen|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.princegeorgecitizen.com/news/local-news/police-seeking-tips-on-suspected-murder-1.21091174|title=Police seeking tips on suspected murder|last=staff|first=Citizen|website=Prince George Citizen|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bc.rcmp-grc.gc.ca/ViewPage.action?siteNodeId=2113&languageId=1&contentId=51868|title=Prince George RCMP \u2013 UPDATE: Homicide \u2013 Roberta Marie SIMS|last=Government of Canada|first=RCMP|date=2017-07-12|website=bc.rcmp-grc.gc.ca|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pgdailynews.ca/index.php/2017/06/02/police-still-looking-into-disappearance-of-roberta-marie-sims/|title=Police still looking into disappearance of Roberta Marie Sims|last=admin|website=pgdailynews.ca|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n|Frances Brown\n|53\n|Missing\n|Smithers\n|2017 (October)\n|Frances was last seen on Saturday 14 October 2017 while out mushroom picking north of Smithers, in the Kitseguecla Rd area. The RCMP suspended its wilderness search effort on 21 October 2017, about nightfall. Nineteen search and rescue crews from around the province were called in, alongside RCMP and local volunteers, to make up what was the largest search operation in the region in years. Evidence of a campfire was discovered early on in the search, but rain and snow hampered the effort. Frances was raised by a trapper and described by family as an experienced back country explorer who spent decades searching for mushrooms in difficult terrain. She was prepared with adequate clothing (rain gear, long johns, hiking boots) and had a lighter. She is deaf in one ear.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bc.rcmp-grc.gc.ca/ViewPage.action?siteNodeId=2100&languageId=1&contentId=53040|title=B.C. RCMP \u2013 Missing Person|last=Division|first=Government of Canada, RCMP, E|website=bc.rcmp-grc.gc.ca|access-date=2018-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/frances-brown-search-suspended-1.4401853|title=Family suspends search for missing mushroom picker as winter weather sets in {{!}} CBC News|work=CBC|access-date=2018-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/we-need-to-bring-frances-home-family-keeps-looking-for-missing-mushroom-picker-after-rcmp-call-off-search-1.4367167|title='We need to bring Frances home': family keeps looking for missing mushroom picker after RCMP call off search {{!}} CBC News|work=CBC|access-date=2018-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bc.missing.report/frances-brown-smithers/|title=MISSING PERSON \u2022 Frances Brown \u2022 Smithers, British Columbia \u2022 53 Years Old|date=2017-10-17|work=British Columbia Missing Report|access-date=2018-12-04}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n|Chantelle Catherine Simpson\n|34\n|Unknown\n|[[Terrace, British Columbia|Terrace]]\n|2018 (July)\n|Chantelle was last seen alive in Telkwa on Wednesday, 4 July 2018. Her abandoned car was located on 5 July by RCMP near a gravel pit on Gossen Creek Street in Terrace. A missing person's bulletin was released by the RCMP on 7 July 2018. Her body was spotted in the Skeena River by a CN conductor. Her body was recovered by Terrace Search and Rescue on 22 July 2018 and identified by tattoos. Exact cause of death is not yet public knowledge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mybulkleylakesnow.com/27080/search-for-telkwas-chantelle-simpson-comes-to-an-end/|title=Search for Telkwa's Chantelle Simpson comes to an end|last=Chartr|first=Taylor|website=My Bulkley Lakes Now|access-date=2018-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.haidagwaiiobserver.com/news/body-of-missing-woman-found-in-skeena-river/|title=Body of missing woman found in Skeena River|date=2018-07-23|website=Haida Gwaii Observer|access-date=2018-12-29}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n|Jessica Patrick (Balczer)\n|18\n|Homicide\n|Smithers\n|2018 (September)\n|Patrick was last seen at the Smithers McDonald's or the Mountainview Motel, early August 31, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bc.ctvnews.ca/missing-smithers-teenager-found-dead-town-mayor-1.4096421|title=Missing Smithers teenager found dead: town mayor|date=2018-09-16|work=British Columbia|access-date=2018-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mybulkleylakesnow.com/28614/missing-smithers-girl/|title=Missing Smithers girl|work=My Bulkley Lakes Now|access-date=2018-09-20}}</ref> Jessica was reported missing on 3 September and an RCMP news release was put out three days later on 6 September.<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.columbiavalleypioneer.com/news/rcmp-confirm-death-of-missing-bc-teen-jessica-patrick/|title=RCMP confirm death of missing BC teen Jessica Patrick \u2013 The Columbia Valley Pioneer|date=2018-09-21|work=The Columbia Valley Pioneer|access-date=2018-10-18}}</ref> News of her death was released on September 16, 2018, before police officially released identity of human remains found.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4455400/human-remains-smithers/|title=Human remains found in Smithers|work=Global News|access-date=2018-09-20}}</ref> RCMP officially released the identity of the remains found on 21 September 2018.<ref name=\":25\" /> According to RCMP, the body was found on Hudson Bay Mountain Road, at a large pull-out, about 15 metres down a steep bank on Saturday, September 15, 2018<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mybulkleylakesnow.com/29090/rcmp-confirm-human-remains-found-last-weekend-are-jessica-patrick-balczers/|title=RCMP confirm human remains found last weekend are Jessica Patrick (Balczer's)|work=My Bulkley Lakes Now|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n|Cynthia Martin\n|50\n|Missing\n|[[Hazelton, British Columbia|Hazelton]]\n|2018 (December)\n|Last seen 23 December 2018 at about 9:00 PM. Family and friends consider her disappearance to be out of character, though RCMP said there was nothing to indicate foul play. The vehicle she was last seen driving was found locked near the Hagwilget Bridge, near Hazelton. Members of Smither's-based Bulkley Valley Search and Rescue carried out an air search over the area on 25 December 2018, with helicopter assistance, but didn't find any trace of Martin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://missingpeople.ca/2018/12/missing-woman-in-new-hazelton-bc-cynthia-martin-50/|title=Missing Woman in New Hazelton, BC \u2013 Cynthia Martin, 50|website=Missing People Canada|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ckpgtoday.ca/article/548908/missing-new-hazelton-woman|title=Missing New Hazelton Woman|date=2018-12-26|website=CKPGToday|language=en|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cfnrfm.ca/2018/12/30/family-of-missing-new-hazelton-woman-remain-hopeful-for-her-safe-return/|title=Family of missing New Hazelton woman remain hopeful for her safe return|last=CFNRNews|website=CFNR Network|language=en|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iheartradio.ca/ez-rock/ez-rock-terrace/news/new-hazelton-woman-missing-1.8634933|title=New Hazelton Woman Missing|last=M\u00e9dia|first=Bell|website=iheartradio.ca|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|}\n\n== Investigation and suspects ==\n[[File:Highway of Tears Corridor.png|alt=Highway of Tears corridor, including some paved egresses from outlying communities to Highway 16.|thumb|Highway of Tears corridor, including some paved egresses from outlying communities to Highway 16.]]\n\nThe first investigation by RCMP that tried to look at Highway of Tears as linked cases was opened in December 1998.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Families wait for new leads in old cases|date=December 2, 1998|publisher = Terrace Standard}}</ref> However, the list of cases as it existed back then included three additional male victims - Larry Vu, Eric Charles Coss and Phillip Innes Fraser,<ref>{{Cite news|title=Terrace resident, Alaskan among open RCMP files|date=December 2, 1998|publisher = Terrace Standard}}</ref> which are not considered linked today.\n\nTo date, a number of people have been convicted in cases related to the Highway of Tears. Three serial killers are among those charged, Brian Peter Arp, Edward Dennis Isaac and [[Cody Legebokoff]].\n\nAlthough he was not implicated in of any Highway of Tears cases, [[Bobby Jack Fowler]] was strongly implicated in a number of cases related to E-Pana, but died in prison before charges could be laid. [[Garry Taylor Handlen]] has been charged with two murders in BC, one of them related to E-Pana. Neither Fowler nor Handlen have been charged in the deaths of any of the Highway of Tears victims. It is also possible that Fowler was linked to the Highway of Tears cases because he worked for a now closed Prince George company called Happy's Roofing in 1974.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ottawacitizen.com/news/Bobby+Jack+Fowler+dead+offender+linked+three+Highway+Tears+murders/7297521/story.html|title=Bobby Jack Fowler, dead U.S. sex offender, linked to three B.C. 'Highway of Tears' murders|first=Lori|last=Culbert|website=www.ottawacitizen.com|accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref> Former Vancouver police geographic profiler [[Kim Rossmo]] is on the record having said that in his opinion Fowler is not responsible for any of the crimes along Highway 16 between 1989 and 2006.<ref name=\":39\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.vancouversun.com/news/Serial+killer+Bobby+Fowler+probably+main+Highway+Tears+murderer+profiler+says/7311075/story.html|title=Serial killer Bobby Fowler probably not the main Highway of Tears murderer, profiler says|last=Culbert|first=Lori|website=vancouversun.com|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, police converged on a property in [[Isle Pierre]], in rural Prince George, to search for the remains of Nicole Hoar, a young tree planter who went missing on Highway 16 on June 21, 2002. The property was once owned by Leland Vincent Switzer, who is currently serving a prison sentence for the second-degree murder of his brother. The RCMP also searched the property for the other missing women from the Highway of Tears; however, no further actions followed the investigation.<ref name=\"beast\" />\n\nRCMP Sgt. Wayne Clary said they may never solve all of the cases and that it will be the \"people in the communities that are going to solve these crimes.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/rcmp-say-mmiw-highway-of-tears-missing-and-murdered-women-cases-may-never-be-solved-1.3805609|title=RCMP say Highway of Tears killers may never be caught|date=October 24, 2016|first=Betsy|last=Trumpener|website=CBC|access-date=2018-12-05}}</ref> They do have persons of interest in several cases, but not enough evidence to lay charges.<ref name=\"LORICULBERT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.canada.com/news/Video+RCMP+believe+there+more+than+Highway+Tears+killer/7296937/story.html|title=Victim's family still heartbroken after dead U.S. sex offender linked to Highway of Tears slaying|last=Culbert|first=Lori|date=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== B.C. Government Email Scandal ==\nIn an official government report, ministerial assistant George Gretes was accused of being irresponsible for \"triple deleting\" all emails relating to the Highway of Tears from the email account of Tim Duncan, former executive assistant to Transportation minister [[Todd Stone]].<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\" />. \n\nOn October 22, 2015, Elizabeth Denham, the Information and Privacy Commissioner of British Columbia, published a 65-page report outlining how B.C. government officials had \"triple deleted\" emails relating to the Highway of Tears.<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\">{{cite web|title=B.C. government 'triple deleted' e-mails related to the Highway of Tears|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/bc-government-triple-deleted-e-mails-related-to-the-highway-of-tears/article26969375/|website=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> In her report ''Access Denied'', Denham describes the act of \"triple deleting\" as transferring an email to the \"deleted\" folder on a computer system, deleting the email from the folder and then overriding the backup that admits the system to retrieve deleted items.<ref>{{cite web|title=B.C. Transportation Minister Todd Stone admits to 'triple deleting' his emails|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/highway-tears-emails-triple-deleted-1.3284985|website=CBC}}</ref> By deleting these files, Denham states the government had breached the Freedom of Information and Protection of Privacy Act.<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\" /> Denham became aware of the scandal in May 2015 after she received a letter from Tim Duncan, the former executive assistant to Transportation Minister [[Todd Stone]].<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\" /> Duncan claimed that as he was responding to an FOI (Freedom of Information) application, ministerial assistant George Gretes ordered for Duncan to search his records for any files pertaining to the Highway of Tears and missing women.<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\" /> Once the files were located, Duncan testified that Gretes ordered for them to be deleted. When Duncan hesitated, Gretes allegedly took the keyboard and \"triple deleted\" all of the emails relating to the Highway of Tears.<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\" /> According to Denham, Gretes originally denied this claim but later admitted to the triple deletion during a second police interview.<ref name=\"cbc.ca\">{{cite web|title=Highway of Tears email deletion referred to RCMP by B.C. privacy watchdog|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/highway-of-tears-email-deletion-referred-to-rcmp-by-b-c-privacy-watchdog-1.3284029|website=CBC}}</ref> Denham states that Gretes\u2014who resigned from his job in October 2015\u2014would have then lied under oath.<ref name=\"cbc.ca\" /> A year earlier in the summer of 2014, a team from the Transportation Ministry toured Highway 16 and conducted numerous meetings with Aboriginal leaders and communities.<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\" /> The significance of this project was to produce safer travel solutions for women living along Highway 16, many of whom had turned to hitchhiking as a way of transportation. In November 2014, the [[New Democratic Party|NDP]] made the FOI request seeking all government files pertaining to missing women, the Highway of Tears and meetings arranged by the ministry: the report Duncan would later respond to.<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\" /> Despite a two-month tour and multiple meetings, the B.C. government claimed the FOI request produced no files relating to the Highway of Tears.<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\" /> According to Denham's report, these records did exist until government officials destroyed them in order to \"skirt freedom of information laws\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Email scandal uncovered a culture of 'delete, delete, delete' in B.C. government|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/email-scandal-1.3284856|website=CBC}}</ref> In ''Access Denied'', Denham called upon the RCMP to further investigate the triple deletion of government files.<ref name=\"cbc.ca\" /> In November 2015, Vancouver lawyer Mark Jett\u00e9 was appointed as special prosecutor within the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police|RCMP]] investigation. Jett\u00e9 will act as the RCMP's independent legal adviser as well as administer an independent assessment of the evidence. He will also pursue any criminal charges that may be found appropriate.<ref>{{cite web|title=Special prosecutor appointed to help investigate triple deletion of emails|url=http://www.cbc.ca/m/touch/canada/britishcolumbia/story/1.3337244|website=CBC}}</ref>\n\nGretes was convicted of one count of lying to the British Columbia privacy commissioner and fined $2,500.<ref>{{cite web:title=Former political aide George Gretes fined $2,500 for misleading B.C.'s privacy commissioner|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/former-political-aide-george-gretes-fined-2500-for-misleading-b-c-s-privacy-commissioner}}</ref>\n\n== Project E-Pana ==\nIn 2005, the RCMP launched a provincially funded project, [[E-Pana]], which started with a focus on some of the unsolved murders and disappearances of young women along Highway 16.<ref name=\"Project E-Pana\">{{cite web|title=Project E-Pana|url=http://bc.cb.rcmp-grc.gc.ca/ViewPage.action?siteNodeId=1525|website=BC RCMP}}</ref> E-Pana sought to discover if there was a single serial killer at work or a multitude of killers operating along the highway.<ref name=\"Project E-Pana\" /> The unit started with 3 cases in 2005, then the unit investigated 9 cases in 2006, but by 2007, its caseload had doubled to 18 and its geographical scope began spanning large parts of the province and not just Highway 16.<ref name=\"Project E-Pana\"/>\n\nThe victims involved within the E-Pana investigation followed the criteria of being female, participating in a high-risk lifestyle, known to hitchhike and were last seen or their bodies were discovered within a mile from Highway 16, [[British Columbia Highway 97|Highway 97]] and [[British Columbia Highway 5|Highway 5]].<ref name=\"Project E-Pana\" /> In the 2009/2010 year, E-Pana received over $5 million in annual funding but has since declined due to budget cutbacks; receiving only $806,109 for the 2013/2014 year.<ref name=\"vancouversun.com\">{{cite web|title=Police budget, officers cut in Highway of Tears probe|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/Police+budget+officers+Highway+Tears+probe/10196415/story.html|website=Vancouver Sun|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> In 2013, Craig Callens, the RCMP deputy commissioner, warned that further budget reductions from the provincial government would greatly affect the Highway of Tears investigations; however, he didn't say this would affect the E-Pana cases which aren't Highway of Tears.<ref>{{cite web|title=E-Pana Announce Significant Development and Request for Public Assistance|url=http://bc.rcmp-grc.gc.ca/ViewPage.action?siteNodeId=50&contentId=27095|website=BC RCMP}}</ref> A 2014 freedom-of-information request stated that the task force had dropped from 70 officers to 12 officers since 2010.<ref name=\"vancouversun.com\" /> E-Pana is responsible for linking the homicide of 16-year-old Colleen MacMillen, who was killed in 1974 with the now-deceased American serial killer [[Bobby Jack Fowler]].<ref name=\"vancouversun.com\"/> E-Pana now considers Fowler a suspect in the murders of two other highway victims, Gale Weys and Pamela Darlington, both of whom were killed in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Victim's family still heartbroken after dead U.S. sex offender linked to Highway of Tears slaying (with video)|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/Video+RCMP+believe+there+more+than+Highway+Tears+killer/7296937/story.html|website=Vancouver Sun|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> In 2014, investigations by E-Pana and the Provincial Unsolved Homicide Unit brought murder charges against Garry Taylor Handlen for the death of 12-year-old Monica Jack in 1978.<ref>{{cite web|title=Garry Taylor Handlen charged in 2 child slaying cold cases|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/garry-taylor-handlen-charged-in-2-child-slaying-cold-cases-1.2856285|website=CBC|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> He was found guilty by jury and sentenced to life in prison in early 2019, thus Monica Jack's murder becomes the first file in Project E-Pana to officially be solved with full court proceedings and sentence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4898814/garry-handlen-sentencing/|title=Garry Handlen sentenced to life in prison, can apply for faint-hope parole in 15 years|website=Global News|accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref> E-Pana is still investigating the remaining unsolved cases although it is unlikely that all will be solved.<ref name=\"vancouversun.com\"/>\n\n== Racism ==\nSome critics argue that the lack of results arising from this investigation is the result of systemic racism.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/westcoastnews/story.html?id=94d7de21-376a-463f-ab96-f41ab1258cee |title=Murder and racism along the Highway of Tears |publisher=Canada.com |date=2009-08-29 |accessdate=2013-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512064103/http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/westcoastnews/story.html?id=94d7de21-376a-463f-ab96-f41ab1258cee |archivedate=2014-05-12 }}</ref> This was also reported to be an issue in the case of [[BC Missing Women Investigation|Vancouver's missing women]] and the [[Robert Pickton]] murders {{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}. The issue of systemic racism in these cases is explored in ''[[Finding Dawn]]'', the 2006 documentary by [[Christine Welsh]] whose film includes a section on the Highway of Tears victim Ramona Wilson, including interviews with family and community members. Often overlooked in reports on the Highway of Tears is the fact that over half of the missing women are [[First Nations]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nActivists argue that media coverage of these cases has been limited, claiming that \"media assign a lesser value to aboriginal women\".<ref name=\"rrj.ca\">Rolston, Adriana (2010). \"Highway of Tears Revisited\" Ryerson Review of Journalism, {{cite web|url=http://www.rrj.ca/m8461/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-10-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305044157/http://rrj.ca/m8461/ |archivedate=2012-03-05 }}</ref> Furthermore, despite the fact that these disappearances date back as far as 1969, it was not until 2005 that [[Project E-Pana]] was launched, investigating similarities between the cases. Nicole Hoar, a Caucasian woman who disappeared in 2002 received a disproportionate amount of media attention at the time of her disappearance. Hers was the first of the Highway of Tears cases to be covered in ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', ''[[Vancouver Sun]]'', and ''[[Edmonton Journal]]''. Gladys Radek, a native activist and the aunt of victim Tamara Chipman, \"believes that if it weren't for Hoar, the police would have invested less effort in investigating cases, and the media would have done little, if anything, to inform the public about the tragedies along the road.\"<ref name=\"rrj.ca\" />\n\n== Recommendation reports ==\nNumerous municipalities and 23 First Nations communities border the Highway of Tears.<ref name=\"news.gov.bc.ca\">{{cite web|url=https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2015TRAN0140-001701|title=Highway 16 Transportation Symposium Focused on Practical Solutions|website=Province of British Columbia|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://britishcolumbia.com/plan-your-trip/regions-and-towns/northern-bc-and-haida-gwaii/yellowhead-highway-16/|title=British Columbia|website=British Columbia}}</ref> The rural region is plagued with poverty and lacks public transportation; many residents turn to [[hitchhike|hitchhiking]] as a form of transit or partake in high risk lifestyles to survive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/b-c-highway-of-tears-study-polls-hitchhikers-habits-1.2653808|title=B.C. Highway of Tears study polls hitchhikers' habits|website=CBC|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nPoverty and a lack of public transit has forced many disadvantaged Aboriginal women to turn to hitchhiking as a cheap means of transportation along Highway 16.<ref>{{cite web|title=What to do about safety on Highway of Tears? B.C. already has its answer|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/what-to-do-about-safety-on-highway-of-tears-bc-already-has-its-answer/article27170780/|website=Globe and Mail|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> Many of the Highway of Tears victims were last seen or reported to be hitchhiking before their disappearances.<ref name=\"hotpdf\" />\nIn March 2006, various Aboriginal groups hosted a two-day Highway of Tears symposium at the CN Center in [[Prince George, British Columbia|Prince George]].<ref name=\"hotpdf\" /> In attendance to the event were the victim's families and over 500 Aboriginal leaders from across British Columbia.<ref name=\"hotpdf\" /> Shortly thereafter, the Highway of Tears Symposium Recommendation Report was issued with 33 recommendations to improve public transit, deter hitchhiking, and prevent violence towards Aboriginal women.<ref name=\"hotpdf\" /> Some of the recommendations from the report include a shuttle bus operation along Highway 16, improved educational, health and social services for Aboriginal people as well counseling and mental health groups organized by Aboriginal workers.<ref name=\"hotpdf\" /> These propositions are part of a long-term recommendation to directly confront the issue of First Nations inter-generational poverty.<ref name=\"hotpdf\" /> The Highway of Tears Symposium Recommendation Report was endorsed by B.C. inquiry commissioner [[Wally Oppal]] in his 2012 Missing Women Commission of Inquiry recommendations.<ref name=\"missingwomeninquiry.ca|website=Missing\">{{cite web|title=Missing Women Commission of Inquiry|url=http://www.missingwomeninquiry.ca|website=Missing Women Inquiry|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> Oppal's public inquiry report into the [[Robert Pickton]] case demanded urgent transportation improvement along Highway 16. Like the Highway of Tears Symposium Recommendation Report, [[Wally Oppal|Oppal's]] report also suggested implementing a shuttle bus service along Highway 16 to deter young women from hitchhiking.<ref name=\"missingwomeninquiry.ca|website=Missing\" />\n\nOn November 24, 2015, the [[First Nations Health Authority]] and B.C. Ministry of Transportation and Infrastructure held the Northern Transportation Symposium in [[Smithers, British Columbia]].<ref name=\"fnha.ca\">{{cite web|title=Highway 16 Transportation Symposium Focused on Practical Solutions|url=http://www.fnha.ca/about/news-and-events/news/highway-16-transportation-symposium-focused-on-practical-solutions|website=First Nations Health Authority|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> The symposium included Aboriginal communities and municipalities along Highway 16 and focused on the issue of medical and non-medical transportation in those regions.<ref name=\"fnha.ca\" /> Discussions included and expanded upon the 2006 Highway of Tears Symposium Recommendation Report and the 2012 Missing Women Commission of Inquiry recommendations.<ref name=\"fnha.ca\" />\n\nIn June 2016, Transportation Minister Todd Stone announced that as the result of collaboration across local communities, a bus service would become available along Highway 16. The project will be joint funded by the federal government and the government of British Columbia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/highway-of-tears-getting-regular-bus-service-1.3637602|title=B.C. government approves regular bus service for Highway of Tears|website=cbc.ca|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, a subsidized transit service began operations on alternating days along a {{convert|400|km|mi}} section between Prince George and Burns Lake.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stewart|first1=Briar|title='Safe, reliable and affordable': New bus service aims to make notorious Highway of Tears less dangerous|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bus-service-bc-highway-of-tears-1.4294249|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Popular culture ==\n[[File:Wow, Maddy Has Been Missing Since 2011 (15829760890).jpg|right|thumb|Awareness campaign for Madison Scott, missing in 2011 along the '''Highway of Tears'''.]]\n\n* ''SERIAL KILLER: Highway of Tears'' is a Crime Junkies podcast that was broadcast December 15, 2019. \n\n* ''Cold Track'' is a script written by a french writer [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1917102/?ref_=fn_al_nm_2 Sylvain Blanchot] based on the Highway Of Tears. \n\n* ''[[Finding Dawn]]'' (2006) is a [[documentary film]] by [[M\u00e9tis people (Canada)|M\u00e9tis]] filmmaker [[Christine Welsh]], about 16-year-old Ramona Wilson, one of the victims found alongside the highway.<ref name=\"Herizons\">{{cite journal|last=O'CONNOR |first=JENNIFER|date=Winter 2009 |title=FINDING DAWN|journal=Herizons|publisher=Bnet|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_7554/is_200901/ai_n32313401/?tag=content;col1}}</ref><ref name=\"CM\">{{cite journal|last=de Vos|first=Gail |date=January 11, 2008 |title=FINDING DAWN|journal=Canadian Materials|publisher=Manitoba Library Association|volume= XIV |issue= 10|url=http://www.umanitoba.ca/outreach/cm/vol14/no10/findingdawn.html}}</ref> Welsh's documentary highlights the reality that Aboriginal women face today: in the past 30 years, an estimated 500 Aboriginal women have gone missing or have been murdered in Canada.<ref name=\"Finding Dawn\">{{cite book|title=Finding Dawn|url=https://www.nfb.ca/film/finding_dawn|publisher=National Film Board|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> Welsh uncovers the social, economic, and historical factors that contribute to this statistic.<ref name=\"Finding Dawn\" /> The film can be accessed online on the Nation Film Board web page.<ref name=\"Finding Dawn\" />\n* ''The Vanishing of Madison Scott'', a documentary produced and directed by [[Steven Scouller]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Vanishing of Madison Scott|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Xn0ROcjh7ys|access-date=2018-12-28|author=Scouller, Steven (Producer/Director)}}</ref>\n* ''[[48 Hours (TV series)|48 Hours]]'': \"Highway of Tears\" (season 25, episode 7), about the Highway of Tears murders, airdate November 17, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Highway of Tears|date=November 17, 2012|work=48 Hours|url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/48-hours-2012/episode-7-season-25/highway-of-tears/195619|accessdate=19 November 2012}}</ref>\n* ''[[Highway of Tears (film)|Highway of Tears]]'' (March 2014), an 80-minute documentary by Canadian filmmakers Matthew Smiley and [[Carly Pope]],<ref name=\"IMDB\">{{cite book|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2175928/ |publisher=IMDb |title=Highway of Tears|date=2014}}</ref> narrated by Canadian actor [[Nathan Fillion]]. The documentary, which was featured in numerous film festivals, raises awareness about the stretch of highway and missing women.<ref>{{cite news|title=Film shines light on 'forgotten' Highway of Tears women|url=https://vancouversun.com/Film+shines+light+forgotten+Highway+Tears+women/10842712/story.html?__lsa=0793-0f86|work=Vancouver Sun}}</ref> In a 2014 interview with CBC, Smiley said that during the editing of the film \"over 400 [indigenous] women were estimated to be missing and or murdered across Canada. By the time we premiered the film, the number was over 600 in March of 2014, then the numbers increased to 900 and now over 1,200 missing and murdered indigenous women across Canada. We cannot turn a blind eye to this.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=''Highway of Tears'' documentary: Q&A with director Matthew Smiley|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/aboriginal/highway-of-tears-documentary-q-a-with-director-matthew-smiley-1.2841080|work=CBC}}</ref>\n* ''Searchers: The Highway of Tears'' (2015), a mini-series produced by the online newscast [[Vice News|VICE]], highlights the story of various Aboriginal women who have disappeared along the Highway of Tears and brings attention to the family, friends, and detectives fighting for justice.<ref>{{cite book|title=Searchers|url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/series/searchers|publisher=VICE}}</ref> VICE also offers online articles pertaining to the Highway of Tears murders and disappearances.<ref>{{cite web|title=SEARCH RESULTS FOR \"HIGHWAY OF TEARS\"|url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/search?query=highway%20of%20tears|website=Vice}}</ref>\n* ''Canada's Missing & Murdered Aboriginal Women'' is a series of 14 short episodes, aired on CBC's flagship news program ''[[The National (CBC)|The National]]''. The series is accessible at ''The National's'' [[YouTube]] channel, under the playlist ''Canada's Missing & Murdered Aboriginal Women''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Canada's Missing & Murdered Aboriginal Women|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLvntPLkd9IMfv0MM4066Rhir2ImBYFAgl|author=''The National'' (CNBC)|publisher=YouTube Playlist|access-date=8 December 2015}}</ref>\n* ''That Lonely Section of Hell: The Botched Investigation of a Serial Killer Who Almost Got Away'' (October 13, 2015),<ref>{{cite book|title=That Lonely Section of Hell: The Botched Investigation of a Serial Killer Who Almost Got Away| author=Shenher, Lorimer |authorlink=Lorimer Shenher|publisher=Greystone Books Ltd|date=October 13, 2015|isbn=978-1-77164-093-0}}</ref> is a memoir for which its author, [[Lorimer Shenher]], was nominated for the B.C. Book Prize. Shenher writes from the perspective of a former reporter and the first police detective to be assigned to the case of the missing women. They also cover the police culture in detail.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Charlie|title=Recovering cop and author Lorimer Shenher richly deserves his nomination for a B.C. Book Prize|url=https://www.straight.com/news/656376/recovering-cop-and-author-lori-shenher-richly-deserves-her-nomination-bc-book-prize|website=Straight.com|publisher=VANCOUVER FREE PRESS|accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref>\n* ''Highway Of Tears'' is the name of a 2011 studio album by Vancouver, BC musician Pernell Reichert<ref>{{cite web|url=https://revelstokemountaineer.com/event/pernell-reichert/|access-date=June 14, 2019|title=Pernell Reichert \u2013 Revelstoke Mountaineer}}</ref> featuring the track ''Highway Of Tears (Song For Nicole)'', a dedication to Nicole Hoar who disappeared in 2002.\n* The ''[[Stacey Dooley|Stacey Dooley Investigates]]'' episode entitled ''Canada\u2019s Lost Girls'', first broadcast on 7 March 2017, where Dooley met the family of Amber Tuccaro, who went missing in 2010 aged 20.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/article/d98ccfcb-4f16-4186-803f-4cd88b7d8f43|title=Why are girls disappearing all over Canada?|first=Catriona|last=White|date=9 March 2017|website=BBC Three|accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://i0.wp.com/vipmedia.globalnews.ca/2013/09/cpt117132151_high.jpg?crop=0px%2C109px%2C544px%2C342px&resize=720%2C480 Image of Bobby Jack Fowler]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140424195804/http://www.highwayoftears.ca/ Private Highway of Tears Website]\n* [http://highwayoftears.org/uploads/Highway%20of%20Tears%20Symposium%20Recommendations%20Report%20-%20January%202013.pdf Highway of Tears Symposium Recommendation Report]\n* [http://www.highwayoftearsfilm.com/ Highway of Tears documentary film Website]\n\n[[Category:Highway of Tears| ]]\n[[Category:Unidentified serial killers]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Unsolved murders in Canada]]\n[[Category:Missing people]]\n[[Category:Crime in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Canadian murderers of children]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Ed WoodWiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eVictims:Spelling/grammar/punctuation/typographical correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Highway_of_Tears"}
{"title_page": "Still Game", "text_new": "{{Short description|BBC television program}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{infobox television\n| show_name = Still Game\n| image = [[File:Still Game Title Card.png|250px]]\n| image_alt =\n| caption = ''Still Game'' title card (series 7\u20139)<br /> (L-R) [[Victor McDade]] and [[Jack Jarvis (Still Game character)|Jack Jarvis]]AJ STYLES DIED\n| genre = [[Sitcom]]\n| camera = [[Multiple-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| channel =\n| picture_format = [[1080i]] [[High-definition television|HDTV]]\n| audio_format =\n| first_run =\n| runtime = 30 minutes\n| creator = [[Ford Kiernan]]<br />[[Greg Hemphill]]\n| developer = Ford Kiernan<br />Greg Hemphill\n| company = [[The Comedy Unit]]<br />[[Effingee Productions]]<br />[[BBC Scotland]]<br />[[BBC Studios]]\n| producer = [[Colin Gilbert]]<br />Michael Hines<br />Ewan Angus<br />Jacqueline Sinclair\n| executive_producer = Ford Kiernan<br />Greg Hemphill<br />[[Steven Canny]]\n| director = [[Michael Hines]]\n| starring = Ford Kiernan<br />Greg Hemphill<br />[[Paul Riley (actor)|Paul Riley]]<br />[[Jane McCarry]]<br />[[Mark Cox (actor)|Mark Cox]]<br />[[Sanjeev Kohli]]<br />[[Gavin Mitchell (actor)|Gavin Mitchell]]<br />[[James Martin (Scottish actor)|James Martin]]\n| theme_music_composer = [[Frank Chacksfield]] and <br/>[[The Cuban Boys]] (2002\u20132007)<br />[[BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra]] (2016\u20132019)\n| opentheme =\n| endtheme =\n| country = [[SCOTLAND]]\n| location = [[Glasgow]], Scotland<br />[[Dumbarton]], Scotland\n| language = [[English language|English]], [[Scots language|Scots]]\n| network = [[BBC One Scotland]] (2002\u20132004, 2006\u20132007) <br />[[BBC Two]] (2005\u20132008)<br/>[[BBC One]] (2005, 2016\u20132019)<br/>[[BBC Scotland (TV channel)|BBC Scotland]] (2019)\n| released =\n| first_aired = {{Start date|2002|9|6|df=yes}}\n| last_aired = {{End date|2019|3|28|df=yes}}\n| num_series = 9\n| num_episodes = 62\n| list_episodes = List of Still Game episodes\n| preceded_by = ''[[Chewin' The Fat]]''\n| followed_by =\n| website = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006qgl8\n}}\n\n'''''Still Game''''' was a Scottish [[sitcom]], produced by [[The Comedy Unit]] with [[BBC Scotland]]. It was created by [[Ford Kiernan]] and [[Greg Hemphill]], who played the lead characters, [[Jack Jarvis (Still Game character)|Jack Jarvis]] and [[Victor McDade]], two [[Glasgow|Glaswegian]] [[pensioner]]s. The characters first appeared in the pair's previous TV sketch show ''[[Chewin' the Fat]]'', which aired in Scotland from January 1999 until December 2005.\n\nFollowing its debut on 6 September 2002, [[List of Still Game episodes|62 episodes]] of ''Still Game'' were aired, including Christmas and [[Hogmanay]] specials. The first three series were broadcast only on [[BBC One Scotland]], though five episodes selected from the first two series were later broadcast throughout the UK on [[BBC Two]] from January to February 2004. From the fourth series, ''Still Game'' was broadcast across the UK on [[BBC Two]]. With the seventh series in 2016, the programme began to be broadcast on [[BBC One]].\n\nIt was announced on 13 July 2018 that a ninth and final series would be produced later in the year which would see the characters go into \"comedy retirement\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BBCScotComms/status/1017544383200153600|title=We're raising a glass, with a tear in our eyes \u2013 it's last orders for #StillGame. The 9th series sees our boys (and Isa) go into comedy retirement in what promises to be a must-see finale. Sob! @BBCScotland @BBCOne @bbcstudios @FordKiernan1 @greghemphill96 @bbccomedypic.twitter.com/7PQXHJLnPI|first=BBC Scotland|last=Comms|date=12 July 2018|publisher=}}</ref> The last day of production was on 14 September 2018, and it started airing on 24 February 2019, being one of the first programmes to be shown on the brand new [[BBC Scotland (TV channel)|BBC Scotland]] channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-46303070|title=TV channel to launch with final Still Game|date=22 November 2018|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Stillgamecover.jpg|thumb|150px|The original stage play of ''Still Game'' (1997\u20131999)]]\n''Still Game'' started as a stage play featuring three characters: Jack Jarvis, Victor McDade, and Winston Ingram. Due to a broken lift, the three men are stranded in Victor's flat and discuss a variety of subjects ranging from death to sex. The stage play toured Scotland, England, Ireland and Canada before returning to Glasgow, where the show was filmed at the Cottiers Theatre in 1999 and released on video on 22 November 1999. A DVD of the show was later released on 2 December 2002\n\nA small number of revisions accompanied ''Still Game'''s transition from stage to television. [[Gavin Mitchell (actor)|Gavin Mitchell]], who originally played Winston (and was replaced by Paul Riley for later performances), played the part of Boabby in the series. Characters mentioned in passing were later fleshed out into supporting characters.\n\nIn 1998, Jack and Victor appeared in a number of skits in a tongue-in-cheek documentary about Scottish [[pop music]] called ''Och Around the Clock''. In these, they are shown to be watching while sitting in Victor's flat. Their skits centred on the duo's disparaging comments about the performers.\n\nThe characters reappeared in Kiernan and Hemphill's sketch show ''[[Chewin' the Fat]]'', nearly every episode of which featured Jack, Victor, Tam and Winston, with minor differences from their counterparts in the series. By the time ''Still Game'' became a show in its own right Winston's physical appearance had changed significantly, but he was still played by [[Paul Riley (actor)|Paul Riley]]. As the show evolved, supporting characters assumed greater prominence. Jack and Victor made their final appearance on ''Chewin' the Fat'' in the 2002 Hogmanay Special.\n\nFor the show's first three series, the broadcast of ''Still Game'' was limited to BBC One Scotland. The show was then moved to BBC Two for the fourth series and shown throughout the UK. On 28 December 2005, the first Christmas special was shown on BBC One, the first national broadcast of the show on the channel. A fifth series of the show started filming in February 2006 and was shown the following June on BBC Two. As of 2006, series three had not been shown nationally, and only five episodes from the first two series were shown on national BBC Two from 17 January to 14 February 2004. The second series was shown nationally from 10 July 2008. This meant it was listed as a new series in TV listings, even though it was not for Scottish viewers.\n\nIn the first three series, the episode titles were all Glaswegian dialect words that were related to the episode. Starting from series four, the episodes were titled using standard English, so that general audiences could understand them.\n\nThe events of ''Still Game'' take place in a [[floating timeline]] where the characters remain the same age from series to series. One of the most prominent examples of this is that Victor reveals that he is 74 years old in \"Scran\", an episode of the second series, but it is not until the fifth series (\"Smoke On The Water\") that he celebrates his 75th birthday.\n\nThe sixth series of ''Still Game'' ended on BBC Two on 23 August 2007. A [[Christmas television special|Christmas special]] was aired on BBC One Scotland on 23 December and for the rest of the UK on BBC Two on 28 December. There was also a Hogmanay special called \"Hootenanny\" aired on BBC One Scotland, later aired to the rest of the UK on 2 January 2008.\n\nFord Kiernan, Greg Hemphill and Paul Riley's company [[Effingee Productions]] is thought to have split up after Riley walked away to go it alone after being refused more control over the future of the company by Kiernan. Hemphill stated that he didn't want a \"boardroom battle\".<ref name=eveningtimes4>{{cite web | title=Evening Times | work=It\u2019s game over for Scots comedy duo | url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/display.var.2447240.0.0.php?act=complaint&cid=1901999 | accessdate=16 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 October 2013, the [[Daily Record (Scotland)|''Daily Record'']] ran a front-page story that the show would be returning. On 23 October 2013, Ford Kiernan and Greg Hemphill announced details of live shows entitled '' Still Game Live'' at [[The SSE Hydro]] in Glasgow at a press conference. They were scheduled to perform four shows beginning in September 2014, but due to high demand, it was extended to 16 and then 21 shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/entertainment/theatre/five-more-dates-added-for-still-games-hydro-show.1385548830|title=Five more dates added for Still Game's Hydro show|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe 21 shows at The Hydro ran from 19 September 2014 until 10 October 2014, played to 210,000 fans and made \u00a36,000,000 in ticket sales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/celebrity/still-game-pulls-6million-21-4417745|title=Still Game pulls in \u00a36million from 21 sell-out shows|first=John|last=Dingwall|date=11 October 2014|publisher=}}</ref> The show received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bigissue.com/reviews/live-reviews/4356/still-game-review| work=The Big Issue| title=STILL GAME \u2013 REVIEW| accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, a special sketch featuring Jack and Victor visiting the set of ''[[River City]]'' was made for [[Children in Need]]. The sketch also featured a cameo of a director played by Still Game director Michael Hines. On [[Hogmanay]] 2014, BBC Scotland showed a documentary celebrating the show titled ''Still Game: The Story So Far''. The programme featured interviews with the cast, celebrities who have appeared on the show and super fans, including a look at some favourite moments.\n\nOn 12 May 2016, the [[BBC]] announced that the show would return in 2016 with a six-part seventh series, nine years after the previous series concluded. Filming of the new seventh series started in the summer and the series began on 7 October 2016.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-36275062 BBC comedy ''Still Game'' to return for new series]</ref> The show's return attracted its highest ever overnight audience for a single episode on 7 October, taking a 58% share of the Scottish TV audience with 1,300,000 viewers. The show also aired for the first time on [[BBC One]] across the UK nationwide and drew a total audience of 3,200,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-37642887|title=Extra performances added to Still Game live show run|date=13 October 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, a second live show ''Still Game Live 2: Bon Voyage'' was announced for the [[SSE Hydro]]. The second stage show was to run for ten nights beginning 4 February 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-37505280|title=Still Game returns with new live shows|date=29 September 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> but in October 2016, a further five performances were added.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-37642887|title=Extra Still Game live shows announced|date=13 October 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Unlike the previous live show, this show was not televised or recorded in any other way.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/FordKiernan1/status/820991574381359104|title=Come and get yer tickets, we are not long away now! We are not recording it so it won't be on telly or dvd'|first=Ford|last=Kiernan|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2017, it was announced that an eighth series has been commissioned to air on [[BBC One]] with plans to broadcast towards the end of 2017.<ref name=\"BBC 16Mar2017\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-39290585 |title=Still Game comedy back for eighth series |date=16 March 2017 |accessdate=16 March 2017}}</ref> The series was pushed back to start on 8 March 2018.\n\nBefore the start of the eighth series, Hemphill revealed that he and Kiernan were about to start writing the ninth series and plan to do a third and final live show after that.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/culture/tv-radio/still-game-gears-up-for-live-show-as-new-series-set-to-screen-1-4700398 |title=Still Game gears up for live show as new series set to screen |date=10 March 2018 |accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 July 2018, the BBC announced that Still Game would return for the ninth and final series later in 2019, after which the show will end. Filming for the ninth series started in August 2018 and was completed on 14 September 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-44807200 |title=Last orders at the Clansman as Still Game returns for final series |date=13 July 2018 |accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=\nhttps://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/still-game-fans-devastated-jane-13243286 |title=Still Game fans devastated as Jane McCarry posts emotional 'last ever call sheet' tweets |date=14 September 2018 |accessdate=7 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe third and final [[SSE Hydro]] live show ''Still Game: The Final Farewell'' was officially announced on 1 November 2018, with five shows in September 2019 taking place over three days.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blog.ticketmaster.co.uk/comedy/still-game-41265/ |title=Still Game announces farewell Glasgow run |date=1 November 2018 |accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref> A further 5 shows were announced on 2 November.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sundaypost.com/fp/five-more-dates-added-for-still-games-final-farewell-show-at-glasgows-sse-hydro-due-to-demand-for-tickets/ |title=Five more dates added for Still Game\u2019s Final Farewell show at Glasgow\u2019s SSE Hydro due to demand for tickets|date=2 November 2018 |accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Series and episodes==\n{{Main|List of Still Game episodes}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto; text-align: center;\"\n! Series || Airdates || Channel\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 1|Series 1]] || 6 September 2002 \u2013 18 October 2002 || rowspan=\"3\"|[[BBC One Scotland]]\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 2|Series 2]] || 28 March 2003 \u2013 23 May 2003\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 3|Series 3]] || 7 May 2004 \u2013 11 June 2004\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 4|Series 4]] || 22 July 2005 \u2013 26 August 2005 || [[BBC Two]]\n|-\n| [[Still Game#Christmas Special (2005)|2005 Christmas Special]] || 28 December 2005 || [[BBC One]]\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 5|Series 5]] || 19 June 2006 \u2013 24 July 2006 || BBC Two\n|-\n| [[Still Game#Hogmanay Special (2006)|2006 Hogmanay Special]] || 31 December 2006 || BBC One Scotland\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 6)|Series 6]] || 12 July 2007 \u2013 23 August 2007 || BBC Two\n|-\n| [[Still Game#Christmas Special (2007)|2007 Christmas Special]] || 23 December 2007 || rowspan=\"4\"|BBC One Scotland\n|-\n| [[Still Game#Hogmanay Special (2007)|2007 Hogmanay Special]] || 31 December 2007\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Live at The Hydro (2014)|2014 Live at the Hydro]] || 7 November 2014\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#The Story So Far|Still Game: The Story So Far]] || 31 December 2014\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 7|Series 7]] || 7 October 2016 \u2013 11 November 2016 || BBC One\n|- \n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 8|Series 8]] || 8 March 2018 \u2013 12 April 2018 || BBC One & [[BBC Two Wales]]\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 9|Series 9]] || 24 February 2019 \u2013 28 March 2019<ref>The first episode aired on Sunday 24 February 2019, the opening night of the new [[BBC Scotland (TV channel)|BBC Scotland]] channel, with subsequent episodes being shown on Thursdays, the last episode in the series being aired on Thursday 28 March 2019.</ref> || [[BBC Scotland (TV channel)|BBC Scotland]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Cast==\n:{{Main|List of Still Game characters}}\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Main cast===\n* [[Ford Kiernan]] as [[Jack Jarvis (Still Game character)|Jack Jarvis]] \n* [[Greg Hemphill]] as [[Victor McDade]]\n* [[Paul Riley (actor)|Paul Riley]] as [[Winston Ingram]]\n* [[Mark Cox (actor)|Mark Cox]] as [[Tam Mullen|Thomas \"Tam\" Mullen]]\n* [[Jane McCarry]] as [[Isa Drennan]]\n* [[Sanjeev Kohli]] as [[Navid Harrid]]\n* [[Gavin Mitchell (actor)|Gavin Mitchell]] as [[List of Still Game characters#Boabby (The Barman) Taylor|Robert \"Boabby The Barman\" Taylor]]<ref>The episode \"Fresh Lick\" refers to his alter ego as Troy the Gardener, a porn star in his younger days.</ref>\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Recurring cast===\n* [[James Martin (Scottish actor)|James Martin]] as \"Auld\" Eric (Jones)\n* [[Paul Young (actor)|Paul Young]] as Hugh \"Shug\" McLaughlin\n* [[Jake D'Arcy]] as Peter \"Pete the Jakey\" McCormack<ref>The episode \"Cauld\" refers to his name being Pete Tain, however in \"Recipe\" his name is McCormack.</ref>\n* Matt Costello as Stevie \"The Bookie\" Reid \n* Shamshad Akhtar as Meena Harrid\n* Lynne McCallum as Peggy McAlpine\n* Sandy Nelson as Chris \"the Postie\" Armstrong\n* Kate Donnelly as Frances Mullen\n* [[Jamie Quinn (actor)|Jamie Quinn]] as Derek \"Fergie\" Ferguson\n* Scott Reid as Michael \"Methadone Mick\" Doherty\n* Marj Hogarth as Fiona Jarvis\n* Bruce Morton as Ian Duncan Sheathing\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Filming locations==\n''Still Game'' is set in the fictional Craiglang area of [[Glasgow]], and the [[Maryhill]] district of the city is a popular filming location. The early part of the first episode \"Flittin\" was filmed in the South Nitshill area of Glasgow, where Jack lived before he moved into the flat next-door to Victor at Osprey Heights. The block of flats which was used to film Osprey Heights can be found at Collina Street in the [[Maryhill]] area of Glasgow. The shops featured in the series can be found in the [[Townhead]] area of Glasgow. The [[Forth and Clyde Canal]] and its locks are used in background shots, along with the nearby high-rise tower blocks (flats) including the one used for Osprey Heights. For the first three series of the show, a pub (\"The Gimlet\") in [[Ruchill]] served as the set exterior of Jenny's pub, originally \"The Clansman\". Between series three and four, the building owner had it demolished. A reproduction exterior set was constructed by the production team in the Glasgow North Media Park, Maryhill for filming starting with the fourth series. An outdoor market in [[Possilpark]] was used in the episode \"Cauld\" when Winston buys several electric heaters. The bingo scene in \"Courtin\" was filmed at the [[Gala Bingo]] hall in Possilpark and was a scene that coincidentally brought two old friends together, as Paul Riley (Winston) and Joe Houston (the Gala Bingo caller featured in filming); were friends in their youth. Scene interiors (Jack and Victor's flats, hallways and the interior of Harrid's) were constructed sets in a warehouse of a complex now a Maryhill industrial estate and part of Craigmont Studios). Scenes from several episodes were also filmed in the [[Knightswood]] area of Glasgow, including exterior scenes in the episode \"Courtin\", and the golf course scenes in the episode \"Tappin\".\n\nFinport, as mentioned and seen in the fifth series, was filmed on location in [[Largs]] and [[Saltcoats]], [[North Ayrshire]], both of which were once popular seaside resorts with Glaswegians. The shots of the promenade and the sea wall is that of Saltcoats' harbour area. The caf\u00e9 that Jack and Victor walk past is The Melbourne Caf\u00e9 in Saltcoats. The pub scene is set in the Royal Oak pub in Largs, while the [[bed and breakfast]] where Jack and Victor stay overnight is located at the north end of Largs promenade. In the scene where Jack and Victor arrive on the bus from the right in Finport, this leads from the sea, as there is no road there. In the scene where Jack and Victor find Winston, a wide panning shot reveals the famous Nardini's ice-cream building and the [[Caledonian MacBrayne]] ferry to [[Millport, Isle of Cumbrae|Millport]].\n\n[[Ardgowan House]], a late eighteenth-century mansion at [[Inverkip]], [[Inverclyde]], was used as the setting for Blairtunnoch in the episode \"Fly Society\". Jack and Victor buy tickets for a meal and evening at the theatre from Tam who won them in a radio quiz. During the pre-theatre meal, they meet two apparently sophisticated, attractive ladies, played by [[Una McLean]] and [[Jeannie Fisher]], whom they try to impress with tall tales of overseas adventures and wealth: the women thus invite them to a country house party at Blairtunnoch.\n\nThe area where Jack and Victor are sitting during the court recess in the episode \"Recipe\" of series six is the Main Lounge of The Crookston Hotel in Glasgow. The interior shots of the bakery in the same episode \"Recipe\" were filmed at factories in Glasgow, one of which [[Tunnocks]] factory in [[Uddingston]] (the baker at the start of this episode is also the Tunnocks baker in Uddingston) and also Pars Foods for the production line scene with Winston.The court scenes were filmed in Court No. 2 of Hamilton Sheriff Court.\n\nThe bar used during the [[Still Game#Hogmanay Special .282007.29|Hogmanay Special in 2007, Hootenanny]], was The Red Hoose in [[Dunipace]], chosen by producers for its old world qualities.\n\nNavid's shop interior was a set in Hillington industrial estate, the exterior shots being a row of shops in Kennedy Path, Townhead, Glasgow.\n\nThe shots where Jack and Victor visit Barbara at her workplace were filmed in [[Clydebank]], a town 8 miles west of Glasgow. The interior of the shop was also filmed on site in a local charity shop which is still in use today.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clyde-shoppingcentre.co.uk/map/storemap.aspx?UnitNo=SWS27&Shopcategory=Miscellaneous|title=Clyde Shopping Centre map|website=www.clyde-shoppingcentre.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nJust before the fifth series started filming, a pest control team had to be called into the Maryhill studio set when it was discovered that rats had infested Navid's shop and were eating their way through the stock. The alarm was raised after [[Jane McCarry]] (Isa) found a dead rat on the set. The high rat population in the area was due to the proximity of the [[Forth and Clyde Canal]].<ref name=\"daily record3\">{{cite web | title=Daily Record | work=A FORD IN THE RIVER | url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/tm_objectid=16708129&method=full&siteid=66633&headline=a-ford-in-the-river--name_page.html/ | accessdate=4 August 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Children In Need]] sketch was filmed on the [[River City|River City set]] at the [[BBC Scotland|BBC Scotland studios]] in [[Dumbarton, Scotland]], as was much of the seventh series.\n\nThe theme music used on the TV broadcasts of the show is an excerpt from \"Cuban Boy\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cubanboys.bandcamp.com/track/cuban-boy-cuban-boys-go-boom-mix|title=Cuban Boy (Cuban Boys Go Boom mix), by Cuban Boys|website=Cuban Boys}}</ref> as recorded by The Cuban Boys, which is itself based on a sample of [[Frank Chacksfield]]'s track of the same name from the album ''West of Sunset''. The opening and ending theme tune was changed to an entirely different theme on the BBC DVD releases: the reason behind this is still unexplained, however licensing could be a possibility. The [[BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra]] recorded an updated version of the theme tune for Series 7, which is also used on the DVD release of that series.\n\n==Awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Group !! Award !! Result\n|-\n| 2003 || Celtic Media Awards || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2004 || Glenfiddich Spirit of Scotland || Most Popular Broadcast || {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Scotland]] || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Rose d'Or]] || Best Sitcom || {{Nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2005 || Celtic Media Awards || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Scotland]] || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Rose d'Or]] || Best Sitcom || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| 2006 || [[BAFTA Scotland]] || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=5|2007 ||rowspan=5|[[BAFTA Scotland]] || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Actor: Sanjeev Kholi || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Actress: Jane McCarry || {{Won}}\n|-\n| TV Writing: Ford Kiernan & Greg Hemphill || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Audience Award || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2008 || [[BAFTA Scotland]] || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2015 || [[BAFTA Scotland]] || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|Scottish Comedy Awards || Best TV Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Best Event: Still Game Live || {{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2017 || Best TV Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n|  [[BAFTA Scotland]] || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Nom}}\n|-\n|  Celtic Media Awards || Best Comedy Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2018 || [[National Television Awards]] || Best Comedy Programme || {{Nom}}\n|-\n||2019 ||Scottish Comedy Awards || Best TV Show ||{{Won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==DVD releases==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"99%\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\"|DVD Title\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Discs\n!rowspan=\"2\"|No. of Ep.\n!DVD release\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Notes\n|-\n![[DVD region code#2|Region 2]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"4CBB17\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 1|Complete Series 1]]'''\n|1\n|6\n|3 July 2006\n|\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"FBEC5D\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 2|Complete Series 2]]'''\n|2\n|9\n|3 July 2006\n|\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"30D5C8\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 3|Complete Series 3]]'''\n|1\n|6\n|17 July 2006\n|\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"C9A0DC\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 4|Complete Series 4]]'''\n|1\n|6\n|17 July 2006\n|Includes behind the scenes footage\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"F88379\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 5|Complete Series 5]]'''\n|1\n|6\n|16 October 2006\n|\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"73C2FB\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 6|Complete Series 6]]'''\n|1\n|7\n|3 September 2007\n|\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"ED1C24\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[Television special|Complete Specials]]'''\n|1\n|4\n|3 November 2008\n|Includes the specials from [[List of Still Game episodes#Christmas Special (2005)|2005]], [[List of Still Game episodes#Hogmanay Special (2006)|2006]] & [[List of Still Game episodes#Christmas Special (2007)|2007]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"FFFFFF\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 1|Complete Series 1]]\u2013[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 5|5]]'''\n|6\n|33\n|16 October 2006\n|\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"FFFFFF\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 1|Complete Series 1]]\u2013[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 6|6]]'''\n|8\n|44\n|3 November 2008\n|Includes all of the specials\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"892E69\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''Still Game Live At The Hydro'''\n|1\n|1\n|24 November 2014\n|Includes over one hour not seen on TV \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"GGGGGG\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 7|Complete Series 7]]'''\n|1\n|6\n|21 November 2016\n| \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"8e56ea\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 8|Complete Series 8]]'''\n|1\n|6\n|16 April 2018\n| \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"f7540e\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 9|Complete Series 9]]'''\n|1\n|6\n|8 April 2019\n| \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"FFFFFF\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes|The Complete Collection]]'''\n|11\n|62\n|8 April 2019\n|Includes all of the specials\n|}\n\n==Critical response==\n\nReferring to the fifth series' finale, Scottish tabloid newspaper the ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'' heralded for ''Still Game'' to be added to the ranks of the \"greatest sitcoms ever\". They called the episode \"classic comedy\" and said it was \"a perfect mix of empathetic friendship, laugh-out-loud gags, real feeling in the acting and genuine warmth and chemistry between the characters\".<ref name=\"daily record2\">{{cite web | title=Daily Record | work=STILL GAME FOR A LAUGH, AND INTO THE BIG LEAGUE | url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/tm_objectid=17457550&method=full&siteid=66633&headline=still-game-for-a-laugh--and-into-the-big-league--name_page.html | accessdate=4 August 2006}}</ref> The Daily Record also reported that ''Still Game'' had higher ratings than rival comedies ''[[The Catherine Tate Show]]'' and [[Steve Coogan|Steve Coogan's]] ''[[Saxondale]]'' with 300,000 and 700,000 more viewers respectively. Creator and star Ford Kiernan said of the ratings: \"I am absolutely delighted. The figures have gradually increased \u2013 episode after episode.\"<ref name=\"daily record1\">{{cite web | title= Daily Record | work=VICTOR IN BEEB RATINGS BATTLE | url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/news/tm_objectid=17395517%26method=full%26siteid=66633-name_page.html | accessdate=4 August 2006}}</ref>\n\n''Still Game'' was criticised for its \"reliance on expletives\" by Teddy Jamieson, [[television]] critic for ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]''. He also commented that the sitcom \"paints [Scotland] in broad strokes\", through its use of [[stereotypes]].<ref name=theherald>{{cite web | title=The Herald | work=Grisly reality of the afterlife | url=http://www.theherald.co.uk/features/66465.html | accessdate= 6 August 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060821224138/http://www.theherald.co.uk/features/66465.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 21 August 2006}}</ref> TV Today praised the show for being \"refreshing\" in the age of dying sitcoms. It said the show was funny in a \"straight down the line way\".<ref name=\"tv today\">{{cite web|title=TV Today |work=Square eyes 24\u201328 July |url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/tvtoday/2006/07/square_eyes_2428_july.php |access-date=4 August 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930184215/http://www.thestage.co.uk/tvtoday/2006/07/square_eyes_2428_july.php |archive-date=30 September 2007 }}</ref> ''Still Game'' has attracted interest from known screen legends, such as [[Sir Sean Connery]] (who even requested a role in the show).<ref name=Scotsman>{{cite web | title=Living.Scotsman.com | work=Still game for a laugh | url=http://living.scotsman.com/tv.cfm?id=882002006 | accessdate=4 August 2006}}</ref> Actor [[Bill Nighy]] is also reported to be a fan, calling upon the distinct Glaswegian accent for his role as [[Davy Jones (Pirates of the Caribbean)|Davy Jones]] in [[Pirates of the Caribbean (film series)|''Pirates of the Caribbean'']].<ref name=dailyrecord4>{{cite web | title=Daily Record | work=SKULL GAME | url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/news/tm_objectid=17342606%26method=full%26siteid=66633-name_page.html | accessdate=4 August 2006}}</ref> The show has won awards in both the 2004 and 2005 ''[[BAFTA Scotland]]'' awards and was named as the winner in the Best Broadcast category at the 2004 [[Glenfiddich Spirit of Scotland Awards]].<ref name=baftas1>{{cite web | title=BAFTA Scotland Awards | work=BAFTA Scotland Awards 2004 Winners | url=http://www.baftascotland.co.uk/htm/2004winners.htm | accessdate= 18 August 2006}}</ref><ref name=baftas2>{{cite web | title=BAFTA Scotland Awards | work=BAFTA Scotland Awards 2005 Winners | url=http://www.baftascotland.co.uk/htm/Awards2005.htm | accessdate=18 August 2006}}</ref><ref name=screenbiz>{{cite web|title=Screenbiz.co.uk |work=THE SPIRIT OF SCOTLAND |url=http://www.screenbiz.co.uk/tvarticles/screentvarticle220.htm |access-date=17 August 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070102000028/http://www.screenbiz.co.uk/tvarticles/screentvarticle220.htm |archive-date=2 January 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, ''Still Game'' was once again nominated for a ''[[BAFTA Scotland]]'' award for the \"Most Popular Television\" category. Other contenders included ''[[Rebus (TV series)|Rebus]]'' and ''[[Taggart]]''.<ref name=\"baftas3\">{{cite web | title=BAFTA Scotland Awards | work=BAFTA Scotland Awards 2006 Winners | url=http://www.baftascotland.co.uk/Awards2006.htm| accessdate=2 November 2006}}</ref> [[Paul Riley (actor)|Paul Riley]], who plays Winston, was also awarded for his role in the show.<ref name=\"chortle\">{{cite web | title=Chortle, the UK comedy guide | work=Game on \u2013 Still Game scoops Scottish Bafta | url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2006/11/13/4690/game_on | accessdate=3 December 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe series revival in 2016 received some negative reviews. Julie McDowall, writing for ''[[The National (Scotland)|The National]]'', said of the first episode \"You're going to hate me for saying this. I already hate myself for even daring to hold these thoughts, but I need to be honest with you: this was a disappointment.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.thenational.scot/culture/14871859.TV_Pick_October_7__Return_of_Still_Game_proves_to_be_a_disappointment/ | work = The National | title = TV Pick October 7: Return of Still Game proves to be a disappointment | accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref> She later said of the series, \"I fear this once brilliant sitcom is turning into ''[[Mrs. Brown's Boys]]''. Just like an auld yin in The Clansman, its teeth have been removed and it\u2019s gumsy and ineffectual and a bit of a bore.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.thenational.scot/culture/14872129.TV_Pick_of_the_Day__Friday__October_14__Still_Game__and_The_Story_of_Skinhead_with_Don_Letts/ | work = The National | title = TV Pick of the Day, Friday, October 14: Still Game, and The Story of Skinhead with Don Letts | accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref> A review in ''Chortle'' said \"I suspect a lot of new viewers will wonder what all the fuss is about, as this episode seems clunky and dated,\" going on to say \"in truth no one here appears to be a great actor\" and that \"it seems to be a little crudely edited, too, with the timing of cutaways off the pace. And when you start to notice things like that, it\u2019s got to be a sign that something\u2019s wrong.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/review/2016/10/07/25957/the_return_of_still_game | work = Chortle | title = The return of Still Game | accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Still Game episodes|List of ''Still Game'' episodes]]\n*[[List of Still Game characters|List of ''Still Game'' characters]]\n*''[[Chewin' the Fat]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{BBC programme}}\n*{{tv.com show|still-game|Still Game}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061213154725/http://www.comedyunit.co.uk/stillgame.asp ''Still Game''] at [[The Comedy Unit]]\n*{{IMDb title|id=0281491|title=Still Game}}\n*{{British Comedy Guide|tv|still_game}}\n*{{epguides|StillGame|Still Game}}\n*[http://www.findthatlocation.com/Television-Show/Still-Game Filming locations from ''Still Game'']\n\n{{Stillgame}}\n\n[[Category:Still Game| ]]\n[[Category:2002 Scottish television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2019 Scottish  television series endings]]\n[[Category:2000s British sitcoms]]\n[[Category:2000s Scottish television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British sitcoms]]\n[[Category:2010s Scottish television series]]\n[[Category:BBC Scotland television programmes]]\n[[Category:BBC television sitcoms]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Scots-language media]]\n[[Category:Scottish satirical television programmes]]\n[[Category:Scottish television sitcoms]]\n[[Category:Television series about old age]]\n[[Category:British television series revived after cancellation]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Maryhill]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|BBC television program}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{infobox television\n| show_name = Still Game\n| image = [[File:Still Game Title Card.png|250px]]\n| image_alt =\n| caption = ''Still Game'' title card (series 7\u20139)<br /> (L-R) [[Victor McDade]] and [[Jack Jarvis (Still Game character)|Jack Jarvis]]\n| genre = [[Sitcom]]\n| camera = [[Multiple-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| channel =\n| picture_format = [[1080i]] [[High-definition television|HDTV]]\n| audio_format =\n| first_run =\n| runtime = 30 minutes\n| creator = [[Ford Kiernan]]<br />[[Greg Hemphill]]\n| developer = Ford Kiernan<br />Greg Hemphill\n| company = [[The Comedy Unit]]<br />[[Effingee Productions]]<br />[[BBC Scotland]]<br />[[BBC Studios]]\n| producer = [[Colin Gilbert]]<br />Michael Hines<br />Ewan Angus<br />Jacqueline Sinclair\n| executive_producer = Ford Kiernan<br />Greg Hemphill<br />[[Steven Canny]]\n| director = [[Michael Hines]]\n| starring = Ford Kiernan<br />Greg Hemphill<br />[[Paul Riley (actor)|Paul Riley]]<br />[[Jane McCarry]]<br />[[Mark Cox (actor)|Mark Cox]]<br />[[Sanjeev Kohli]]<br />[[Gavin Mitchell (actor)|Gavin Mitchell]]<br />[[James Martin (Scottish actor)|James Martin]]\n| theme_music_composer = [[Frank Chacksfield]] and <br/>[[The Cuban Boys]] (2002\u20132007)<br />[[BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra]] (2016\u20132019)\n| opentheme =\n| endtheme =\n| country = [[SCOTLAND]]\n| location = [[Glasgow]], Scotland<br />[[Dumbarton]], Scotland\n| language = [[English language|English]], [[Scots language|Scots]]\n| network = [[BBC One Scotland]] (2002\u20132004, 2006\u20132007) <br />[[BBC Two]] (2005\u20132008)<br/>[[BBC One]] (2005, 2016\u20132019)<br/>[[BBC Scotland (TV channel)|BBC Scotland]] (2019)\n| released =\n| first_aired = {{Start date|2002|9|6|df=yes}}\n| last_aired = {{End date|2019|3|28|df=yes}}\n| num_series = 9\n| num_episodes = 62\n| list_episodes = List of Still Game episodes\n| preceded_by = ''[[Chewin' The Fat]]''\n| followed_by =\n| website = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006qgl8\n}}\n\n'''''Still Game''''' was a Scottish [[sitcom]], produced by [[The Comedy Unit]] with [[BBC Scotland]]. It was created by [[Ford Kiernan]] and [[Greg Hemphill]], who played the lead characters, [[Jack Jarvis (Still Game character)|Jack Jarvis]] and [[Victor McDade]], two [[Glasgow|Glaswegian]] [[pensioner]]s. The characters first appeared in the pair's previous TV sketch show ''[[Chewin' the Fat]]'', which aired in Scotland from January 1999 until December 2005.\n\nFollowing its debut on 6 September 2002, [[List of Still Game episodes|62 episodes]] of ''Still Game'' were aired, including Christmas and [[Hogmanay]] specials. The first three series were broadcast only on [[BBC One Scotland]], though five episodes selected from the first two series were later broadcast throughout the UK on [[BBC Two]] from January to February 2004. From the fourth series, ''Still Game'' was broadcast across the UK on [[BBC Two]]. With the seventh series in 2016, the programme began to be broadcast on [[BBC One]].\n\nIt was announced on 13 July 2018 that a ninth and final series would be produced later in the year which would see the characters go into \"comedy retirement\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BBCScotComms/status/1017544383200153600|title=We're raising a glass, with a tear in our eyes \u2013 it's last orders for #StillGame. The 9th series sees our boys (and Isa) go into comedy retirement in what promises to be a must-see finale. Sob! @BBCScotland @BBCOne @bbcstudios @FordKiernan1 @greghemphill96 @bbccomedypic.twitter.com/7PQXHJLnPI|first=BBC Scotland|last=Comms|date=12 July 2018|publisher=}}</ref> The last day of production was on 14 September 2018, and it started airing on 24 February 2019, being one of the first programmes to be shown on the brand new [[BBC Scotland (TV channel)|BBC Scotland]] channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-46303070|title=TV channel to launch with final Still Game|date=22 November 2018|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Stillgamecover.jpg|thumb|150px|The original stage play of ''Still Game'' (1997\u20131999)]]\n''Still Game'' started as a stage play featuring three characters: Jack Jarvis, Victor McDade, and Winston Ingram. Due to a broken lift, the three men are stranded in Victor's flat and discuss a variety of subjects ranging from death to sex. The stage play toured Scotland, England, Ireland and Canada before returning to Glasgow, where the show was filmed at the Cottiers Theatre in 1999 and released on video on 22 November 1999. A DVD of the show was later released on 2 December 2002\n\nA small number of revisions accompanied ''Still Game'''s transition from stage to television. [[Gavin Mitchell (actor)|Gavin Mitchell]], who originally played Winston (and was replaced by Paul Riley for later performances), played the part of Boabby in the series. Characters mentioned in passing were later fleshed out into supporting characters.\n\nIn 1998, Jack and Victor appeared in a number of skits in a tongue-in-cheek documentary about Scottish [[pop music]] called ''Och Around the Clock''. In these, they are shown to be watching while sitting in Victor's flat. Their skits centred on the duo's disparaging comments about the performers.\n\nThe characters reappeared in Kiernan and Hemphill's sketch show ''[[Chewin' the Fat]]'', nearly every episode of which featured Jack, Victor, Tam and Winston, with minor differences from their counterparts in the series. By the time ''Still Game'' became a show in its own right Winston's physical appearance had changed significantly, but he was still played by [[Paul Riley (actor)|Paul Riley]]. As the show evolved, supporting characters assumed greater prominence. Jack and Victor made their final appearance on ''Chewin' the Fat'' in the 2002 Hogmanay Special.\n\nFor the show's first three series, the broadcast of ''Still Game'' was limited to BBC One Scotland. The show was then moved to BBC Two for the fourth series and shown throughout the UK. On 28 December 2005, the first Christmas special was shown on BBC One, the first national broadcast of the show on the channel. A fifth series of the show started filming in February 2006 and was shown the following June on BBC Two. As of 2006, series three had not been shown nationally, and only five episodes from the first two series were shown on national BBC Two from 17 January to 14 February 2004. The second series was shown nationally from 10 July 2008. This meant it was listed as a new series in TV listings, even though it was not for Scottish viewers.\n\nIn the first three series, the episode titles were all Glaswegian dialect words that were related to the episode. Starting from series four, the episodes were titled using standard English, so that general audiences could understand them.\n\nThe events of ''Still Game'' take place in a [[floating timeline]] where the characters remain the same age from series to series. One of the most prominent examples of this is that Victor reveals that he is 74 years old in \"Scran\", an episode of the second series, but it is not until the fifth series (\"Smoke On The Water\") that he celebrates his 75th birthday.\n\nThe sixth series of ''Still Game'' ended on BBC Two on 23 August 2007. A [[Christmas television special|Christmas special]] was aired on BBC One Scotland on 23 December and for the rest of the UK on BBC Two on 28 December. There was also a Hogmanay special called \"Hootenanny\" aired on BBC One Scotland, later aired to the rest of the UK on 2 January 2008.\n\nFord Kiernan, Greg Hemphill and Paul Riley's company [[Effingee Productions]] is thought to have split up after Riley walked away to go it alone after being refused more control over the future of the company by Kiernan. Hemphill stated that he didn't want a \"boardroom battle\".<ref name=eveningtimes4>{{cite web | title=Evening Times | work=It\u2019s game over for Scots comedy duo | url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/display.var.2447240.0.0.php?act=complaint&cid=1901999 | accessdate=16 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 October 2013, the [[Daily Record (Scotland)|''Daily Record'']] ran a front-page story that the show would be returning. On 23 October 2013, Ford Kiernan and Greg Hemphill announced details of live shows entitled '' Still Game Live'' at [[The SSE Hydro]] in Glasgow at a press conference. They were scheduled to perform four shows beginning in September 2014, but due to high demand, it was extended to 16 and then 21 shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/entertainment/theatre/five-more-dates-added-for-still-games-hydro-show.1385548830|title=Five more dates added for Still Game's Hydro show|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe 21 shows at The Hydro ran from 19 September 2014 until 10 October 2014, played to 210,000 fans and made \u00a36,000,000 in ticket sales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/celebrity/still-game-pulls-6million-21-4417745|title=Still Game pulls in \u00a36million from 21 sell-out shows|first=John|last=Dingwall|date=11 October 2014|publisher=}}</ref> The show received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bigissue.com/reviews/live-reviews/4356/still-game-review| work=The Big Issue| title=STILL GAME \u2013 REVIEW| accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, a special sketch featuring Jack and Victor visiting the set of ''[[River City]]'' was made for [[Children in Need]]. The sketch also featured a cameo of a director played by Still Game director Michael Hines. On [[Hogmanay]] 2014, BBC Scotland showed a documentary celebrating the show titled ''Still Game: The Story So Far''. The programme featured interviews with the cast, celebrities who have appeared on the show and super fans, including a look at some favourite moments.\n\nOn 12 May 2016, the [[BBC]] announced that the show would return in 2016 with a six-part seventh series, nine years after the previous series concluded. Filming of the new seventh series started in the summer and the series began on 7 October 2016.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-36275062 BBC comedy ''Still Game'' to return for new series]</ref> The show's return attracted its highest ever overnight audience for a single episode on 7 October, taking a 58% share of the Scottish TV audience with 1,300,000 viewers. The show also aired for the first time on [[BBC One]] across the UK nationwide and drew a total audience of 3,200,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-37642887|title=Extra performances added to Still Game live show run|date=13 October 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, a second live show ''Still Game Live 2: Bon Voyage'' was announced for the [[SSE Hydro]]. The second stage show was to run for ten nights beginning 4 February 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-37505280|title=Still Game returns with new live shows|date=29 September 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> but in October 2016, a further five performances were added.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-37642887|title=Extra Still Game live shows announced|date=13 October 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Unlike the previous live show, this show was not televised or recorded in any other way.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/FordKiernan1/status/820991574381359104|title=Come and get yer tickets, we are not long away now! We are not recording it so it won't be on telly or dvd'|first=Ford|last=Kiernan|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2017, it was announced that an eighth series has been commissioned to air on [[BBC One]] with plans to broadcast towards the end of 2017.<ref name=\"BBC 16Mar2017\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-39290585 |title=Still Game comedy back for eighth series |date=16 March 2017 |accessdate=16 March 2017}}</ref> The series was pushed back to start on 8 March 2018.\n\nBefore the start of the eighth series, Hemphill revealed that he and Kiernan were about to start writing the ninth series and plan to do a third and final live show after that.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/culture/tv-radio/still-game-gears-up-for-live-show-as-new-series-set-to-screen-1-4700398 |title=Still Game gears up for live show as new series set to screen |date=10 March 2018 |accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 July 2018, the BBC announced that Still Game would return for the ninth and final series later in 2019, after which the show will end. Filming for the ninth series started in August 2018 and was completed on 14 September 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-44807200 |title=Last orders at the Clansman as Still Game returns for final series |date=13 July 2018 |accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=\nhttps://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/still-game-fans-devastated-jane-13243286 |title=Still Game fans devastated as Jane McCarry posts emotional 'last ever call sheet' tweets |date=14 September 2018 |accessdate=7 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe third and final [[SSE Hydro]] live show ''Still Game: The Final Farewell'' was officially announced on 1 November 2018, with five shows in September 2019 taking place over three days.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blog.ticketmaster.co.uk/comedy/still-game-41265/ |title=Still Game announces farewell Glasgow run |date=1 November 2018 |accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref> A further 5 shows were announced on 2 November.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sundaypost.com/fp/five-more-dates-added-for-still-games-final-farewell-show-at-glasgows-sse-hydro-due-to-demand-for-tickets/ |title=Five more dates added for Still Game\u2019s Final Farewell show at Glasgow\u2019s SSE Hydro due to demand for tickets|date=2 November 2018 |accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Series and episodes==\n{{Main|List of Still Game episodes}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto; text-align: center;\"\n! Series || Airdates || Channel\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 1|Series 1]] || 6 September 2002 \u2013 18 October 2002 || rowspan=\"3\"|[[BBC One Scotland]]\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 2|Series 2]] || 28 March 2003 \u2013 23 May 2003\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 3|Series 3]] || 7 May 2004 \u2013 11 June 2004\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 4|Series 4]] || 22 July 2005 \u2013 26 August 2005 || [[BBC Two]]\n|-\n| [[Still Game#Christmas Special (2005)|2005 Christmas Special]] || 28 December 2005 || [[BBC One]]\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 5|Series 5]] || 19 June 2006 \u2013 24 July 2006 || BBC Two\n|-\n| [[Still Game#Hogmanay Special (2006)|2006 Hogmanay Special]] || 31 December 2006 || BBC One Scotland\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 6)|Series 6]] || 12 July 2007 \u2013 23 August 2007 || BBC Two\n|-\n| [[Still Game#Christmas Special (2007)|2007 Christmas Special]] || 23 December 2007 || rowspan=\"4\"|BBC One Scotland\n|-\n| [[Still Game#Hogmanay Special (2007)|2007 Hogmanay Special]] || 31 December 2007\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Live at The Hydro (2014)|2014 Live at the Hydro]] || 7 November 2014\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#The Story So Far|Still Game: The Story So Far]] || 31 December 2014\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 7|Series 7]] || 7 October 2016 \u2013 11 November 2016 || BBC One\n|- \n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 8|Series 8]] || 8 March 2018 \u2013 12 April 2018 || BBC One & [[BBC Two Wales]]\n|-\n| [[List of Still Game episodes#Series 9|Series 9]] || 24 February 2019 \u2013 28 March 2019<ref>The first episode aired on Sunday 24 February 2019, the opening night of the new [[BBC Scotland (TV channel)|BBC Scotland]] channel, with subsequent episodes being shown on Thursdays, the last episode in the series being aired on Thursday 28 March 2019.</ref> || [[BBC Scotland (TV channel)|BBC Scotland]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Cast==\n:{{Main|List of Still Game characters}}\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Main cast===\n* [[Ford Kiernan]] as [[Jack Jarvis (Still Game character)|Jack Jarvis]] \n* [[Greg Hemphill]] as [[Victor McDade]]\n* [[Paul Riley (actor)|Paul Riley]] as [[Winston Ingram]]\n* [[Mark Cox (actor)|Mark Cox]] as [[Tam Mullen|Thomas \"Tam\" Mullen]]\n* [[Jane McCarry]] as [[Isa Drennan]]\n* [[Sanjeev Kohli]] as [[Navid Harrid]]\n* [[Gavin Mitchell (actor)|Gavin Mitchell]] as [[List of Still Game characters#Boabby (The Barman) Taylor|Robert \"Boabby The Barman\" Taylor]]<ref>The episode \"Fresh Lick\" refers to his alter ego as Troy the Gardener, a porn star in his younger days.</ref>\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Recurring cast===\n* [[James Martin (Scottish actor)|James Martin]] as \"Auld\" Eric (Jones)\n* [[Paul Young (actor)|Paul Young]] as Hugh \"Shug\" McLaughlin\n* [[Jake D'Arcy]] as Peter \"Pete the Jakey\" McCormack<ref>The episode \"Cauld\" refers to his name being Pete Tain, however in \"Recipe\" his name is McCormack.</ref>\n* Matt Costello as Stevie \"The Bookie\" Reid \n* Shamshad Akhtar as Meena Harrid\n* Lynne McCallum as Peggy McAlpine\n* Sandy Nelson as Chris \"the Postie\" Armstrong\n* Kate Donnelly as Frances Mullen\n* [[Jamie Quinn (actor)|Jamie Quinn]] as Derek \"Fergie\" Ferguson\n* Scott Reid as Michael \"Methadone Mick\" Doherty\n* Marj Hogarth as Fiona Jarvis\n* Bruce Morton as Ian Duncan Sheathing\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Filming locations==\n''Still Game'' is set in the fictional Craiglang area of [[Glasgow]], and the [[Maryhill]] district of the city is a popular filming location. The early part of the first episode \"Flittin\" was filmed in the South Nitshill area of Glasgow, where Jack lived before he moved into the flat next-door to Victor at Osprey Heights. The block of flats which was used to film Osprey Heights can be found at Collina Street in the [[Maryhill]] area of Glasgow. The shops featured in the series can be found in the [[Townhead]] area of Glasgow. The [[Forth and Clyde Canal]] and its locks are used in background shots, along with the nearby high-rise tower blocks (flats) including the one used for Osprey Heights. For the first three series of the show, a pub (\"The Gimlet\") in [[Ruchill]] served as the set exterior of Jenny's pub, originally \"The Clansman\". Between series three and four, the building owner had it demolished. A reproduction exterior set was constructed by the production team in the Glasgow North Media Park, Maryhill for filming starting with the fourth series. An outdoor market in [[Possilpark]] was used in the episode \"Cauld\" when Winston buys several electric heaters. The bingo scene in \"Courtin\" was filmed at the [[Gala Bingo]] hall in Possilpark and was a scene that coincidentally brought two old friends together, as Paul Riley (Winston) and Joe Houston (the Gala Bingo caller featured in filming); were friends in their youth. Scene interiors (Jack and Victor's flats, hallways and the interior of Harrid's) were constructed sets in a warehouse of a complex now a Maryhill industrial estate and part of Craigmont Studios). Scenes from several episodes were also filmed in the [[Knightswood]] area of Glasgow, including exterior scenes in the episode \"Courtin\", and the golf course scenes in the episode \"Tappin\".\n\nFinport, as mentioned and seen in the fifth series, was filmed on location in [[Largs]] and [[Saltcoats]], [[North Ayrshire]], both of which were once popular seaside resorts with Glaswegians. The shots of the promenade and the sea wall is that of Saltcoats' harbour area. The caf\u00e9 that Jack and Victor walk past is The Melbourne Caf\u00e9 in Saltcoats. The pub scene is set in the Royal Oak pub in Largs, while the [[bed and breakfast]] where Jack and Victor stay overnight is located at the north end of Largs promenade. In the scene where Jack and Victor arrive on the bus from the right in Finport, this leads from the sea, as there is no road there. In the scene where Jack and Victor find Winston, a wide panning shot reveals the famous Nardini's ice-cream building and the [[Caledonian MacBrayne]] ferry to [[Millport, Isle of Cumbrae|Millport]].\n\n[[Ardgowan House]], a late eighteenth-century mansion at [[Inverkip]], [[Inverclyde]], was used as the setting for Blairtunnoch in the episode \"Fly Society\". Jack and Victor buy tickets for a meal and evening at the theatre from Tam who won them in a radio quiz. During the pre-theatre meal, they meet two apparently sophisticated, attractive ladies, played by [[Una McLean]] and [[Jeannie Fisher]], whom they try to impress with tall tales of overseas adventures and wealth: the women thus invite them to a country house party at Blairtunnoch.\n\nThe area where Jack and Victor are sitting during the court recess in the episode \"Recipe\" of series six is the Main Lounge of The Crookston Hotel in Glasgow. The interior shots of the bakery in the same episode \"Recipe\" were filmed at factories in Glasgow, one of which [[Tunnocks]] factory in [[Uddingston]] (the baker at the start of this episode is also the Tunnocks baker in Uddingston) and also Pars Foods for the production line scene with Winston.The court scenes were filmed in Court No. 2 of Hamilton Sheriff Court.\n\nThe bar used during the [[Still Game#Hogmanay Special .282007.29|Hogmanay Special in 2007, Hootenanny]], was The Red Hoose in [[Dunipace]], chosen by producers for its old world qualities.\n\nNavid's shop interior was a set in Hillington industrial estate, the exterior shots being a row of shops in Kennedy Path, Townhead, Glasgow.\n\nThe shots where Jack and Victor visit Barbara at her workplace were filmed in [[Clydebank]], a town 8 miles west of Glasgow. The interior of the shop was also filmed on site in a local charity shop which is still in use today.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clyde-shoppingcentre.co.uk/map/storemap.aspx?UnitNo=SWS27&Shopcategory=Miscellaneous|title=Clyde Shopping Centre map|website=www.clyde-shoppingcentre.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nJust before the fifth series started filming, a pest control team had to be called into the Maryhill studio set when it was discovered that rats had infested Navid's shop and were eating their way through the stock. The alarm was raised after [[Jane McCarry]] (Isa) found a dead rat on the set. The high rat population in the area was due to the proximity of the [[Forth and Clyde Canal]].<ref name=\"daily record3\">{{cite web | title=Daily Record | work=A FORD IN THE RIVER | url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/tm_objectid=16708129&method=full&siteid=66633&headline=a-ford-in-the-river--name_page.html/ | accessdate=4 August 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Children In Need]] sketch was filmed on the [[River City|River City set]] at the [[BBC Scotland|BBC Scotland studios]] in [[Dumbarton, Scotland]], as was much of the seventh series.\n\nThe theme music used on the TV broadcasts of the show is an excerpt from \"Cuban Boy\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cubanboys.bandcamp.com/track/cuban-boy-cuban-boys-go-boom-mix|title=Cuban Boy (Cuban Boys Go Boom mix), by Cuban Boys|website=Cuban Boys}}</ref> as recorded by The Cuban Boys, which is itself based on a sample of [[Frank Chacksfield]]'s track of the same name from the album ''West of Sunset''. The opening and ending theme tune was changed to an entirely different theme on the BBC DVD releases: the reason behind this is still unexplained, however licensing could be a possibility. The [[BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra]] recorded an updated version of the theme tune for Series 7, which is also used on the DVD release of that series.\n\n==Awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Group !! Award !! Result\n|-\n| 2003 || Celtic Media Awards || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2004 || Glenfiddich Spirit of Scotland || Most Popular Broadcast || {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Scotland]] || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Rose d'Or]] || Best Sitcom || {{Nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2005 || Celtic Media Awards || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Scotland]] || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Rose d'Or]] || Best Sitcom || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| 2006 || [[BAFTA Scotland]] || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=5|2007 ||rowspan=5|[[BAFTA Scotland]] || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Actor: Sanjeev Kholi || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Actress: Jane McCarry || {{Won}}\n|-\n| TV Writing: Ford Kiernan & Greg Hemphill || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Audience Award || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2008 || [[BAFTA Scotland]] || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2015 || [[BAFTA Scotland]] || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|Scottish Comedy Awards || Best TV Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Best Event: Still Game Live || {{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2017 || Best TV Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n|  [[BAFTA Scotland]] || Best Entertainment Programme || {{Nom}}\n|-\n|  Celtic Media Awards || Best Comedy Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2018 || [[National Television Awards]] || Best Comedy Programme || {{Nom}}\n|-\n||2019 ||Scottish Comedy Awards || Best TV Show ||{{Won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==DVD releases==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"99%\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\"|DVD Title\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Discs\n!rowspan=\"2\"|No. of Ep.\n!DVD release\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Notes\n|-\n![[DVD region code#2|Region 2]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"4CBB17\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 1|Complete Series 1]]'''\n|1\n|6\n|3 July 2006\n|\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"FBEC5D\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 2|Complete Series 2]]'''\n|2\n|9\n|3 July 2006\n|\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"30D5C8\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 3|Complete Series 3]]'''\n|1\n|6\n|17 July 2006\n|\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"C9A0DC\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 4|Complete Series 4]]'''\n|1\n|6\n|17 July 2006\n|Includes behind the scenes footage\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"F88379\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 5|Complete Series 5]]'''\n|1\n|6\n|16 October 2006\n|\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"73C2FB\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 6|Complete Series 6]]'''\n|1\n|7\n|3 September 2007\n|\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"ED1C24\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[Television special|Complete Specials]]'''\n|1\n|4\n|3 November 2008\n|Includes the specials from [[List of Still Game episodes#Christmas Special (2005)|2005]], [[List of Still Game episodes#Hogmanay Special (2006)|2006]] & [[List of Still Game episodes#Christmas Special (2007)|2007]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"FFFFFF\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 1|Complete Series 1]]\u2013[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 5|5]]'''\n|6\n|33\n|16 October 2006\n|\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"FFFFFF\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 1|Complete Series 1]]\u2013[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 6|6]]'''\n|8\n|44\n|3 November 2008\n|Includes all of the specials\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"892E69\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''Still Game Live At The Hydro'''\n|1\n|1\n|24 November 2014\n|Includes over one hour not seen on TV \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"GGGGGG\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 7|Complete Series 7]]'''\n|1\n|6\n|21 November 2016\n| \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"8e56ea\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 8|Complete Series 8]]'''\n|1\n|6\n|16 April 2018\n| \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"f7540e\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes#Series 9|Complete Series 9]]'''\n|1\n|6\n|8 April 2019\n| \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"FFFFFF\" height=\"10px\"|\n|'''[[List of Still Game episodes|The Complete Collection]]'''\n|11\n|62\n|8 April 2019\n|Includes all of the specials\n|}\n\n==Critical response==\n\nReferring to the fifth series' finale, Scottish tabloid newspaper the ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'' heralded for ''Still Game'' to be added to the ranks of the \"greatest sitcoms ever\". They called the episode \"classic comedy\" and said it was \"a perfect mix of empathetic friendship, laugh-out-loud gags, real feeling in the acting and genuine warmth and chemistry between the characters\".<ref name=\"daily record2\">{{cite web | title=Daily Record | work=STILL GAME FOR A LAUGH, AND INTO THE BIG LEAGUE | url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/tm_objectid=17457550&method=full&siteid=66633&headline=still-game-for-a-laugh--and-into-the-big-league--name_page.html | accessdate=4 August 2006}}</ref> The Daily Record also reported that ''Still Game'' had higher ratings than rival comedies ''[[The Catherine Tate Show]]'' and [[Steve Coogan|Steve Coogan's]] ''[[Saxondale]]'' with 300,000 and 700,000 more viewers respectively. Creator and star Ford Kiernan said of the ratings: \"I am absolutely delighted. The figures have gradually increased \u2013 episode after episode.\"<ref name=\"daily record1\">{{cite web | title= Daily Record | work=VICTOR IN BEEB RATINGS BATTLE | url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/news/tm_objectid=17395517%26method=full%26siteid=66633-name_page.html | accessdate=4 August 2006}}</ref>\n\n''Still Game'' was criticised for its \"reliance on expletives\" by Teddy Jamieson, [[television]] critic for ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]''. He also commented that the sitcom \"paints [Scotland] in broad strokes\", through its use of [[stereotypes]].<ref name=theherald>{{cite web | title=The Herald | work=Grisly reality of the afterlife | url=http://www.theherald.co.uk/features/66465.html | accessdate= 6 August 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060821224138/http://www.theherald.co.uk/features/66465.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 21 August 2006}}</ref> TV Today praised the show for being \"refreshing\" in the age of dying sitcoms. It said the show was funny in a \"straight down the line way\".<ref name=\"tv today\">{{cite web|title=TV Today |work=Square eyes 24\u201328 July |url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/tvtoday/2006/07/square_eyes_2428_july.php |access-date=4 August 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930184215/http://www.thestage.co.uk/tvtoday/2006/07/square_eyes_2428_july.php |archive-date=30 September 2007 }}</ref> ''Still Game'' has attracted interest from known screen legends, such as [[Sir Sean Connery]] (who even requested a role in the show).<ref name=Scotsman>{{cite web | title=Living.Scotsman.com | work=Still game for a laugh | url=http://living.scotsman.com/tv.cfm?id=882002006 | accessdate=4 August 2006}}</ref> Actor [[Bill Nighy]] is also reported to be a fan, calling upon the distinct Glaswegian accent for his role as [[Davy Jones (Pirates of the Caribbean)|Davy Jones]] in [[Pirates of the Caribbean (film series)|''Pirates of the Caribbean'']].<ref name=dailyrecord4>{{cite web | title=Daily Record | work=SKULL GAME | url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/news/tm_objectid=17342606%26method=full%26siteid=66633-name_page.html | accessdate=4 August 2006}}</ref> The show has won awards in both the 2004 and 2005 ''[[BAFTA Scotland]]'' awards and was named as the winner in the Best Broadcast category at the 2004 [[Glenfiddich Spirit of Scotland Awards]].<ref name=baftas1>{{cite web | title=BAFTA Scotland Awards | work=BAFTA Scotland Awards 2004 Winners | url=http://www.baftascotland.co.uk/htm/2004winners.htm | accessdate= 18 August 2006}}</ref><ref name=baftas2>{{cite web | title=BAFTA Scotland Awards | work=BAFTA Scotland Awards 2005 Winners | url=http://www.baftascotland.co.uk/htm/Awards2005.htm | accessdate=18 August 2006}}</ref><ref name=screenbiz>{{cite web|title=Screenbiz.co.uk |work=THE SPIRIT OF SCOTLAND |url=http://www.screenbiz.co.uk/tvarticles/screentvarticle220.htm |access-date=17 August 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070102000028/http://www.screenbiz.co.uk/tvarticles/screentvarticle220.htm |archive-date=2 January 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, ''Still Game'' was once again nominated for a ''[[BAFTA Scotland]]'' award for the \"Most Popular Television\" category. Other contenders included ''[[Rebus (TV series)|Rebus]]'' and ''[[Taggart]]''.<ref name=\"baftas3\">{{cite web | title=BAFTA Scotland Awards | work=BAFTA Scotland Awards 2006 Winners | url=http://www.baftascotland.co.uk/Awards2006.htm| accessdate=2 November 2006}}</ref> [[Paul Riley (actor)|Paul Riley]], who plays Winston, was also awarded for his role in the show.<ref name=\"chortle\">{{cite web | title=Chortle, the UK comedy guide | work=Game on \u2013 Still Game scoops Scottish Bafta | url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2006/11/13/4690/game_on | accessdate=3 December 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe series revival in 2016 received some negative reviews. Julie McDowall, writing for ''[[The National (Scotland)|The National]]'', said of the first episode \"You're going to hate me for saying this. I already hate myself for even daring to hold these thoughts, but I need to be honest with you: this was a disappointment.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.thenational.scot/culture/14871859.TV_Pick_October_7__Return_of_Still_Game_proves_to_be_a_disappointment/ | work = The National | title = TV Pick October 7: Return of Still Game proves to be a disappointment | accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref> She later said of the series, \"I fear this once brilliant sitcom is turning into ''[[Mrs. Brown's Boys]]''. Just like an auld yin in The Clansman, its teeth have been removed and it\u2019s gumsy and ineffectual and a bit of a bore.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.thenational.scot/culture/14872129.TV_Pick_of_the_Day__Friday__October_14__Still_Game__and_The_Story_of_Skinhead_with_Don_Letts/ | work = The National | title = TV Pick of the Day, Friday, October 14: Still Game, and The Story of Skinhead with Don Letts | accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref> A review in ''Chortle'' said \"I suspect a lot of new viewers will wonder what all the fuss is about, as this episode seems clunky and dated,\" going on to say \"in truth no one here appears to be a great actor\" and that \"it seems to be a little crudely edited, too, with the timing of cutaways off the pace. And when you start to notice things like that, it\u2019s got to be a sign that something\u2019s wrong.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/review/2016/10/07/25957/the_return_of_still_game | work = Chortle | title = The return of Still Game | accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Still Game episodes|List of ''Still Game'' episodes]]\n*[[List of Still Game characters|List of ''Still Game'' characters]]\n*''[[Chewin' the Fat]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{BBC programme}}\n*{{tv.com show|still-game|Still Game}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061213154725/http://www.comedyunit.co.uk/stillgame.asp ''Still Game''] at [[The Comedy Unit]]\n*{{IMDb title|id=0281491|title=Still Game}}\n*{{British Comedy Guide|tv|still_game}}\n*{{epguides|StillGame|Still Game}}\n*[http://www.findthatlocation.com/Television-Show/Still-Game Filming locations from ''Still Game'']\n\n{{Stillgame}}\n\n[[Category:Still Game| ]]\n[[Category:2002 Scottish television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2019 Scottish  television series endings]]\n[[Category:2000s British sitcoms]]\n[[Category:2000s Scottish television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British sitcoms]]\n[[Category:2010s Scottish television series]]\n[[Category:BBC Scotland television programmes]]\n[[Category:BBC television sitcoms]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Scots-language media]]\n[[Category:Scottish satirical television programmes]]\n[[Category:Scottish television sitcoms]]\n[[Category:Television series about old age]]\n[[Category:British television series revived after cancellation]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Maryhill]]\n", "name_user": "AJ styles died", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Still_Game"}
